# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: retro-6502-assembly
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **8-bit** integers or other data units are those that are 8 bits wide (1 octet).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] Also, 8-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers or data buses of that size.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] Memory addresses (and thus address buses) for 8-bit CPUs are generally larger than 8-bit, usually 16-bit.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] 8-bit microcomputers are microcomputers that use 8-bit microprocessors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] The term '8-bit' is also applied to the character sets that could be used on computers with 8-bit bytes, the best known being various forms of extended ASCII, including the ISO/IEC 8859 series of national character sets – especially Latin 1 for English and Western European languages.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] The IBM System/360 introduced byte-addressable memory with 8-bit bytes, as opposed to bit-addressable or decimal digit-addressable or word-addressable memory, although its general-purpose registers were 32 bits wide, and addresses were contained in the lower 24 bits of those addresses.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] Different models of System/360 had different internal data path widths; the IBM System/360 Model 30 (1965) implemented the 32-bit System/360 architecture, but had an 8-bit native path width, and performed 32-bit arithmetic 8 bits at a time.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] The first widely adopted 8-bit microprocessor was the Intel 8080, being used in many hobbyist computers of the late 1970s and early 1980s, often running the CP/M operating system; it had 8-bit data words and 16-bit addresses.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] The Zilog Z80 (compatible with the 8080) and the Motorola 6800 were also used in similar computers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] The Z80 and the MOS Technology 6502 8-bit CPUs were widely used in home computers and second- and third-generation game consoles of the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] Many 8-bit CPUs or microcontrollers are the basis of today's ubiquitous embedded systems.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] 8-bit microprocessors were the first widely used microprocessors in the computing industry, marking a major shift from mainframes and minicomputers to smaller, more affordable systems.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] The introduction of 8-bit processors in the 1970s enabled the production of personal computers, leading to the popularization of computing and setting the foundation for the modern computing landscape.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] The 1976 Zilog Z80, one of the most popular 8-bit CPUs (though with 4-bit ALU, at least in the original), was discontinued in 2024 (its product line Z84C00), with Last Time Buy (LTB) orders by 14 June 2024.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] An 8-bit register can store 28 different values.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] The range of integer values that can be stored in 8 bits depends on the integer representation used.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] With the two most common representations, the range is 0 through 255 (28 − 1) for representation as an (unsigned) binary number, and −128 (−1 × 27) through 127 (27 − 1) for representation as two's complement.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] 8-bit CPUs use an 8-bit data bus and can therefore access 8 bits of data in a single machine instruction.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] The address bus is typically a double octet (16 bits) wide, due to practical and economical considerations.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] This implies a direct address space of 64 KB (65,536 bytes) on most 8-bit processors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] Most home computers from the 8-bit era fully exploited the address space, such as the BBC Micro (Model B) with 32 KB of RAM plus 32 KB of ROM.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] The Commodore 128, and other 8-bit systems, meaning still with 16-bit addressing, could use more than 64 KB, i.e.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] 128 KB RAM, also the BBC Master with it expandable to 512 KB of RAM.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] Some index registers, such as the two in the 6502, are 8-bit.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] This limits the size of the arrays addressed using indexed addressing instructions to objects of up to 256 bytes (28 bytes) without requiring more complicated code.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] Other 8-bit CPUs, such as the Motorola 6800 and Intel 8080, have 16-bit index registers.*"Interview with William Mensch, 1995 October 09".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] *Silicon Genesis: Oral Histories of Semiconductor Technology*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] The first commercial 8-bit processor was the Intel 8008 (1972) which was originally intended for the Datapoint 2200 intelligent terminal.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] Most competitors to Intel started off with such character oriented 8-bit microprocessors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] Modernized variants of these 8-bit machines are still one of the most common types of processor in embedded systems.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] The MOS Technology 6502, and variants of it, were used in personal computers, such as the Apple I, Apple II, Atari 8-bit computers, BBC Micro, PET, VIC-20, and in home video game consoles such as the Atari 2600 and the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] 8-bit processors continue to be designed for general education about computer hardware, as well as for hobbyists' interests.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] One such CPU was designed and implemented using 7400-series integrated circuits on a breadboard.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/8-bit-computing] Designing 8-bit CPUs and their respective assemblers is a common training exercise for engineering students, engineers, and hobbyists.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language usually has one statement per machine code instruction (1:1), but constants, comments, assembler directives, symbolic labels of, e.g., memory locations, registers, and macros are generally also supported.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The first assembly code in which a language is used to represent machine code instructions is found in Kathleen and Andrew Donald Booth's 1947 work, *Coding for A.R.C.*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly code is converted into executable machine code by a utility program referred to as an *assembler*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The term "assembler" is generally attributed to Wilkes, Wheeler and Gill in their 1951 book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer*, who, however, used the term to mean "a program that assembles another program consisting of several sections into a single program".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The conversion process is referred to as *assembly*, as in *assembling* the source code.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The computational step when an assembler is processing a program is called *assembly time*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Because assembly depends on the machine code instructions, each assembly language is specific to a particular computer architecture such as x86 or ARM.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes there is more than one assembler for the same architecture, and sometimes an assembler is specific to an operating system or to particular operating systems.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most assembly languages do not provide specific syntax for operating system calls, and most assembly languages can be used universally with any operating system, as the language provides access to all the real capabilities of the processor, upon which all system call mechanisms ultimately rest.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In contrast to assembly languages, most high-level programming languages are generally portable across multiple architectures but require interpreting or compiling, much more complicated tasks than assembling.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In the first decades of computing, it was commonplace for both systems programming and application programming to take place entirely in assembly language.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] While still irreplaceable for some purposes, the majority of programming is now conducted in higher-level interpreted and compiled languages.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In "No Silver Bullet", Fred Brooks summarised the effects of the switch away from assembly language programming: "Surely the most powerful stroke for software productivity, reliability, and simplicity has been the progressive use of high-level languages for programming.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Today, it is typical to use small amounts of assembly language code within larger systems implemented in a higher-level language, for performance reasons or to interact directly with hardware in ways unsupported by the higher-level language.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, just under 2% of version 4.9 of the Linux kernel source code is written in assembly; more than 97% is written in C.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language uses mnemonic symbols to represent low-level machine instructions (opcodes), directives, and usually architectural registers and flags.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some of the mnemonics may be built-in and some user-defined.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Many operations require one or more operands in order to form a complete instruction.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers permit named constants, registers, and labels for program and memory locations, and can calculate expressions for operands.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Thus, programmers are freed from tedious repetitive calculations and assembler programs are much more readable than machine code.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Depending on the architecture, these elements may also be combined for specific instructions or addressing modes using offsets or other data as well as fixed addresses.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers offer additional mechanisms to facilitate program development, to control the assembly process, and to aid debugging.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some are column oriented, with specific fields in specific columns; this was very common for machines using punched cards in the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers have free-form syntax, with fields separated by delimiters, e.g., punctuation, white space.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers are hybrid, with, e.g., labels, in a specific column and other fields separated by delimiters; this became more common than column-oriented syntax in the 1960s.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] An **assembler** program creates object code by translating combinations of mnemonics and syntax for operations and addressing modes into their numerical equivalents.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This representation typically includes an *operation code* ("opcode") as well as other control bits and data.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The assembler also calculates constant expressions and resolves symbolic names for memory locations and other entities.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The use of symbolic references is a key feature of assemblers, saving tedious calculations and manual address updates after program modifications.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers also include macro facilities for performing textual substitution – e.g., to generate common short sequences of instructions as inline, instead of *called* subroutines.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers may also be able to perform some simple types of instruction set-specific optimizations.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] One concrete example of this may be the ubiquitous x86 assemblers from various vendors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Called jump-sizing, most of them are able to perform jump-instruction replacements (long jumps replaced by short or relative jumps) in any number of passes, on request.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Others may even do simple rearrangement or insertion of instructions, such as some assemblers for RISC architectures that can help optimize a sensible instruction scheduling to exploit the CPU pipeline as efficiently as possible.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assemblers have been available since the 1950s, as the first step above machine language and before high-level programming languages such as Fortran, Algol, COBOL and Lisp.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There have also been several classes of translators and semi-automatic code generators with properties similar to both assembly and high-level languages, with Speedcode as perhaps one of the better-known examples.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There may be several assemblers with different syntax for a particular CPU or instruction set architecture.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, an instruction to add memory data to a register in a x86-family processor might be `add eax,[ebx]`, in original *Intel syntax*, whereas this would be written `addl (%ebx),%eax` in the *AT&T syntax* used by the GNU Assembler.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Despite different appearances, different syntactic forms generally generate the same numeric machine code.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A single assembler may also have different modes in order to support variations in syntactic forms as well as their exact semantic interpretations (such as FASM-syntax, TASM-syntax, ideal mode, etc., in the special case of x86 assembly programming).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There are two types of assemblers based on how many passes through the source are needed (how many times the assembler reads the source) to produce the object file.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In both cases, the assembler must be able to determine the size of each instruction on the initial passes in order to calculate the addresses of subsequent symbols.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In an assembler with peephole optimization, addresses may be recalculated between passes to allow replacing pessimistic code with code tailored to the exact distance from the target.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The original reason for the use of one-pass assemblers was memory size and speed of assembly – often a second pass would require storing the symbol table in memory (to handle forward references), rewinding and rereading the program source on tape, or rereading a deck of cards or punched paper tape.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Later computers with much larger memories (especially disc storage), had the space to perform all necessary processing without such re-reading.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The advantage of the multi-pass assembler is that the absence of errata makes the linking process (or the program load if the assembler directly produces executable code) faster.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] See Language design below for more details.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A program written in assembly language consists of a series of mnemonic processor instructions and meta-statements (known variously as declarative operations, directives, pseudo-instructions, pseudo-operations and pseudo-ops), comments and data.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language instructions usually consist of an opcode mnemonic followed by an operand, which might be a list of data, arguments or parameters.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some instructions may be "implied", which means the data upon which the instruction operates is implicitly defined by the instruction itself—such an instruction does not take an operand.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The resulting statement is translated by an assembler into machine language instructions that can be loaded into memory and executed.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, the instruction below tells an x86/IA-32 processor to move an immediate 8-bit value into a register.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The binary code for this instruction is 10110 followed by a 3-bit identifier for which register to use.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The identifier for the *AL* register is 000, so the following machine code loads the *AL* register with the data 01100001.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This binary computer code can be made more human-readable by expressing it in hexadecimal as follows.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Here, `B0` means "Move a copy of the following value into *AL*", and `61` is a hexadecimal representation of the value 01100001, which is 97 in decimal.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language for the 8086 family provides the mnemonic MOV (an abbreviation of *move*) for instructions such as this, so the machine code above can be written as follows in assembly language, complete with an explanatory comment if required, after the semicolon.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This is much easier to read and to remember.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Other assemblers may use separate opcode mnemonics such as L for "move memory to register", ST for "move register to memory", LR for "move register to register", MVI for "move immediate operand to memory", etc.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] If the same mnemonic is used for different instructions, that means that the mnemonic corresponds to several different binary instruction codes, excluding data (e.g. the `61h` in this example), depending on the operands that follow the mnemonic.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, for the x86/IA-32 CPUs, the Intel assembly language syntax `MOV AL, AH` represents an instruction that moves the contents of register *AH* into register *AL*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The first byte, 88h, identifies a move between a byte-sized register and either another register or memory, and the second byte, E0h, is encoded (with three bit-fields) to specify that both operands are registers, the source is *AH*, and the destination is *AL*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In a case like this where the same mnemonic can represent more than one binary instruction, the assembler determines which instruction to generate by examining the operands.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In the first example, the operand `61h` is a valid hexadecimal numeric constant and is not a valid register name, so only the `B0` instruction can be applicable.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In the second example, the operand `AH` is a valid register name and not a valid numeric constant (hexadecimal, decimal, octal, or binary), so only the `88` instruction can be applicable.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages are always designed so that this sort of lack of ambiguity is universally enforced by their syntax.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, in the Intel x86 assembly language, a hexadecimal constant must start with a numeral digit, so that the hexadecimal number 'A' (equal to decimal ten) would be written as `0Ah` or `0AH`, not `AH`, specifically so that it cannot appear to be the name of register *AH*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Returning to the original example, while the x86 opcode 10110000 (`B0`) copies an 8-bit value into the *AL* register, 10110001 (`B1`) moves it into *CL* and 10110010 (`B2`) does so into *DL*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language examples for these follow.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The syntax of MOV can also be more complex as the following examples show.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In each case, the MOV mnemonic is translated directly into one of the opcodes 88-8C, 8E, A0-A3, B0-BF, C6 or C7 by an assembler, and the programmer normally does not have to know or remember which.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] An assembler transforms assembly language into machine code, and the reverse can at least partially be achieved by a disassembler.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Unlike high-level languages, there is a one-to-one correspondence between many simple assembly statements and machine language instructions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] However, in some cases, an assembler may provide *pseudoinstructions* (essentially macros) which expand into several machine language instructions to provide commonly needed functionality.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, for a machine that lacks a "branch if greater or equal" instruction, an assembler may provide a pseudoinstruction that expands to the machine's "set if less than" and "branch if zero (on the result of the set instruction)".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most full-featured assemblers also provide a rich macro language (discussed below) which is used by vendors and programmers to generate more complex code and data sequences.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Likewise, since comments in the assembly language source file are ignored by the assembler and have no effect on the object code it generates, a disassembler is always completely unable to recover source comments.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Each computer architecture has its own machine language.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Computers differ in the number and type of operations they support, in the different sizes and numbers of registers, and in the representations of data in storage.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] While most general-purpose computers are able to carry out essentially the same functionality, the ways they do so differ; the corresponding assembly languages reflect these differences.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Multiple sets of mnemonics or assembly-language syntax may exist for a single instruction set, typically instantiated in different assembler programs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In these cases, the most popular one is usually that supplied by the CPU manufacturer and used in its documentation.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Two examples of CPUs that have two different sets of mnemonics are the Intel 8080 family and the Intel 8086/8088.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Because Intel claimed copyright on its assembly language mnemonics (on each page of their documentation published in the 1970s and early 1980s, at least), some companies that independently produced CPUs compatible with Intel instruction sets invented their own mnemonics.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The Zilog Z80 CPU, an enhancement of the Intel 8080A, supports all the 8080A instructions plus many more; Zilog invented an entirely new assembly language, not only for the new instructions but also for all of the 8080A instructions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For example, where Intel uses the mnemonics *MOV*, *MVI*, *LDA*, *STA*, *LXI*, *LDAX*, *STAX*, *LHLD*, and *SHLD* for various data transfer instructions, the Z80 assembly language uses the mnemonic *LD* for all of them.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A similar case is the NEC V20 and V30 CPUs, enhanced copies of the Intel 8086 and 8088, respectively.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Like Zilog with the Z80, NEC invented new mnemonics for all of the 8086 and 8088 instructions, to avoid accusations of infringement of Intel's copyright.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] "Hello, world!" can be printed using 32-bit assembly language for an x86 processor with little help from an operating system.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] "Call outchr" calls some mechanism that prints a character in AL to the console.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A non zero-length string must be terminated with a byte of zero.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There is a large degree of diversity in the way the authors of assemblers categorize statements and in the nomenclature that they use.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In particular, some describe anything other than a machine mnemonic or extended mnemonic as a pseudo-operation (pseudo-op).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Instructions (statements) in assembly language are generally very simple, unlike those in high-level languages.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Generally, a mnemonic is a symbolic name for a single executable machine language instruction (an opcode), and there is at least one opcode mnemonic defined for each machine language instruction.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Each instruction typically consists of an *operation* or *opcode* plus zero or more *operands*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Most instructions refer to a single value or a pair of values.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Operands can be immediate (value coded in the instruction itself), registers specified in the instruction or implied, or the addresses of data located elsewhere in storage.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This is determined by the underlying processor architecture: the assembler merely reflects how this architecture works.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] *Extended mnemonics* are often used to specify a combination of an opcode with a specific operand, e.g., the System/360 assemblers use `B` as an extended mnemonic for `BC` with a mask of 15 and `NOP` ("NO OPeration" – do nothing for one step) for `BC` with a mask of 0.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers also support simple built-in macro-instructions that generate two or more machine instructions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, with some Z80 assemblers the instruction `ld hl,bc` is recognized to generate `ld l,c` followed by `ld h,b`.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] These are sometimes known as *pseudo-opcodes*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Mnemonics are arbitrary symbols; in 1985 the IEEE published Standard 694 for a uniform set of mnemonics to be used by all assemblers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There are instructions used to define data elements to hold data and variables.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] They define the type of data, the length and the alignment of data.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] These instructions can also define whether the data is available to outside programs (programs assembled separately) or only to the program in which the data section is defined.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers classify these as pseudo-ops.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly directives, also called pseudo-opcodes, pseudo-operations or pseudo-ops, are commands given to an assembler "directing it to perform operations other than assembling instructions".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Directives affect how the assembler operates and "may affect the object code, the symbol table, the listing file, and the values of internal assembler parameters".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes the term *pseudo-opcode* is reserved for directives that generate object code, such as those that generate data.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The names of pseudo-ops often start with a dot to distinguish them from machine instructions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Pseudo-ops can make the assembly of the program dependent on parameters input by a programmer, so that one program can be assembled in different ways, perhaps for different applications.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Or, a pseudo-op can be used to manipulate presentation of a program to make it easier to read and maintain.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Another common use of pseudo-ops is to reserve storage areas for run-time data and optionally initialize their contents to known values.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Symbolic assemblers let programmers associate arbitrary names (*labels* or *symbols*) with memory locations and various constants.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Usually, every constant and variable is given a name so instructions can reference those locations by name, thus promoting self-documenting code.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In executable code, the name of each subroutine is associated with its entry point, so any calls to a subroutine can use its name.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Inside subroutines, GOTO destinations are given labels.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers support *local symbols* which are often lexically distinct from normal symbols (e.g., the use of "10$" as a GOTO destination).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers, such as NASM, provide flexible symbol management, letting programmers manage different namespaces, automatically calculate offsets within data structures, and assign labels that refer to literal values or the result of simple computations performed by the assembler.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Labels can also be used to initialize constants and variables with relocatable addresses.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages, like most other computer languages, allow comments to be added to program source code that will be ignored during assembly.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Judicious commenting is essential in assembly language programs, as the meaning and purpose of a sequence of binary machine instructions can be difficult to determine.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The "raw" (uncommented) assembly language generated by compilers or disassemblers is quite difficult to read when changes must be made.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers support *predefined macros*, and others support *programmer-defined* (and repeatedly re-definable) macros involving sequences of text lines in which variables and constants are embedded.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The macro definition is most commonly a mixture of assembler statements, e.g., directives, symbolic machine instructions, and templates for assembler statements.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This sequence of text lines may include opcodes or directives.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Once a macro has been defined its name may be used in place of a mnemonic.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] When the assembler processes such a statement, it replaces the statement with the text lines associated with that macro, then processes them as if they existed in the source code file (including, in some assemblers, expansion of any macros existing in the replacement text).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macros in this sense date to IBM autocoders of the 1950s.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In assembly language, the term "macro" represents a more comprehensive concept than it does in some other contexts, such as the pre-processor in the C programming language, where its #define directive typically is used to create short single line macros.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembler macro instructions, like macros in PL/I and some other languages, can be lengthy "programs" by themselves, executed by interpretation by the assembler during assembly.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Since macros can have 'short' names but expand to several or indeed many lines of code, they can be used to make assembly language programs appear to be far shorter, requiring fewer lines of source code, as with higher level languages.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] They can also be used to add higher levels of structure to assembly programs, optionally introduce embedded debugging code via parameters and other similar features.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macro assemblers often allow macros to take parameters.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Thus a macro might generate numerous assembly language instructions or data definitions, based on the macro arguments.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This could be used to generate record-style data structures or "unrolled" loops, for example, or could generate entire algorithms based on complex parameters.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] For instance, a "sort" macro could accept the specification of a complex sort key and generate code crafted for that specific key, not needing the run-time tests that would be required for a general procedure interpreting the specification.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] An organization using assembly language that has been heavily extended using such a macro suite can be considered to be working in a higher-level language since such programmers are not working with a computer's lowest-level conceptual elements.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Underlining this point, macros were used to implement an early virtual machine in SNOBOL4 (1967), which was written in the SNOBOL Implementation Language (SIL), an assembly language for a virtual machine.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The target machine would translate this to its native code using a macro assembler.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This allowed a high degree of portability for the time.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macros were used to customize large scale software systems for specific customers in the mainframe era and were also used by customer personnel to satisfy their employers' needs by making specific versions of manufacturer operating systems.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] IBM OS/360 uses macros to perform system generation.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The user specifies options by coding a series of assembler macros.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Assembling these macros generates a job stream to build the system, including job control language and utility control statements.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This is because, as was realized in the 1960s, the concept of "macro processing" is independent of the concept of "assembly", the former being in modern terms more word processing, text processing, than generating object code.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The concept of macro processing appeared, and appears, in the C programming language, which supports "preprocessor instructions" to set variables, and make conditional tests on their values.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Unlike certain previous macro processors inside assemblers, the C preprocessor is not Turing-complete because it lacks the ability to either loop or "go to", the latter allowing programs to loop.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Despite the power of macro processing, it fell into disuse in many high level languages (major exceptions being C, C++ and PL/I) while remaining a perennial for assemblers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Macro parameter substitution is strictly by name: at macro processing time, the value of a parameter is textually substituted for its name.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The most famous class of bugs resulting was the use of a parameter that itself was an expression and not a simple name when the macro writer expected a name.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] the intention was that the caller would provide the name of a variable, and the "global" variable or constant b would be used to multiply "a".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] If foo is called with the parameter `a-c`, the macro expansion of `load a-c*b` occurs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] To avoid any possible ambiguity, users of macro processors can parenthesize formal parameters inside macro definitions, or callers can parenthesize the input parameters.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Packages of macros have been written providing structured programming elements to encode execution flow.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The earliest example of this approach was in the Concept-14 macro set, originally proposed by Harlan Mills (March 1970), and implemented by Marvin Kessler at IBM's Federal Systems Division, which provided IF/ELSE/ENDIF and similar control flow blocks for OS/360 assembler programs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This was a way to reduce or eliminate the use of GOTO operations in assembly code, one of the main factors causing spaghetti code in assembly language.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] This approach was widely accepted in the early 1980s (the latter days of large-scale assembly language use).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] IBM's High Level Assembler Toolkit includes such a macro package.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Another design was A-Natural, a "stream-oriented" assembler for 8080/Z80 processors from Whitesmiths Ltd.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] (developers of the Unix-like Idris operating system, and what was reported to be the first commercial C compiler).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] The language was classified as an assembler because it worked with raw machine elements such as opcodes, registers, and memory references; but it incorporated an expression syntax to indicate execution order.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] Parentheses and other special symbols, along with block-oriented structured programming constructs, controlled the sequence of the generated instructions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] A-natural was built as the object language of a C compiler, rather than for hand-coding, but its logical syntax won some fans.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] There has been little apparent demand for more sophisticated assemblers since the decline of large-scale assembly language development.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p01] In spite of that, they are still being developed and applied in cases where resource constraints or peculiarities in the target system's architecture prevent the effective use of higher-level languages.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] When the stored-program computer was introduced, programs were written in machine code, and loaded into the computer from punched paper tape or toggled directly into memory from console switches.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] In late 1948, the Electronic Delay Storage Automatic Calculator (EDSAC) had an assembler (named "initial orders") integrated into its bootstrap program.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] It used one-letter mnemonics developed by David Wheeler, who is credited by the IEEE Computer Society as the creator of the first "assembler".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Reports on the EDSAC introduced the term "assembly" for the process of combining fields into an instruction word.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] SOAP (Symbolic Optimal Assembly Program) was an assembly language for the IBM 650 computer written by Stan Poley in 1955.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly languages eliminated much of the error-prone, tedious, and time-consuming first-generation programming needed with the earliest computers, freeing programmers from tedium such as remembering numeric codes and calculating addresses.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] They were once widely used for all sorts of programming.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] By the late 1950s their use had largely been supplanted by higher-level languages in the search for improved programming productivity.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Today, assembly language is still used for direct hardware manipulation, access to specialized processor instructions, or to address critical performance issues.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Typical uses are device drivers, low-level embedded systems, and real-time systems (see § Current usage).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Numerous programs were written entirely in assembly language.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] The Burroughs MCP (1961) was the first computer for which an operating system was not developed entirely in assembly language; it was written in Executive Systems Problem Oriented Language (ESPOL), an Algol dialect.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Many commercial applications were written in assembly language as well, including a large amount of the IBM mainframe software developed by large corporations.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] COBOL, FORTRAN and some PL/I eventually displaced assembly language, although a number of large organizations retained assembly-language application infrastructures well into the 1990s.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the primary development language for 8-bit home computers such as the Apple II, Atari 8-bit computers, ZX Spectrum, and Commodore 64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Interpreted BASIC on these systems did not offer maximum execution speed and full use of facilities to take full advantage of the available hardware.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the default choice for programming 8-bit consoles such as the Atari 2600 and Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Key software for IBM PC compatibles such as MS-DOS, Turbo Pascal, and the Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet was written in assembly language.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] As computer speed grew exponentially, assembly language became a tool for speeding up parts of programs, such as the rendering of *Doom*, rather than a dominant development language.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] In the 1990s, assembly language was used to maximise performance from systems such as the Sega Saturn, and as the primary language for arcade hardware using the TMS34010 integrated CPU/GPU such as *Mortal Kombat* and *NBA Jam*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] There has been debate over the usefulness and performance of assembly language relative to high-level languages.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Although assembly language has specific niche uses where it is important (see below), there are other tools for optimization.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] As of July 2017, the TIOBE index of programming language popularity ranks assembly language at 11, ahead of Visual Basic, for example.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembler can be used to optimize for speed or optimize for size.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] In the case of speed optimization, modern optimizing compilers are claimed to render high-level languages into code that can run as fast as hand-written assembly, despite some counter-examples.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] The complexity of modern processors and memory sub-systems makes effective optimization increasingly difficult for compilers and assembly programmers alike.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Increasing processor performance has meant that most CPUs sit idle most of the time, with delays caused by predictable bottlenecks such as cache misses, I/O operations and paging, making raw code execution speed a non-issue for many programmers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language is still taught in most computer science and electronic engineering programs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Although few programmers today regularly work with assembly language as a tool, the underlying concepts remain important.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Such fundamental topics as binary arithmetic, memory allocation, stack processing, character set encoding, interrupt processing, and compiler design would be hard to study in detail without a grasp of how a computer operates at the hardware level.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Since a computer's behaviour is fundamentally defined by its instruction set, the logical way to learn such concepts is to study an assembly language.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Most modern computers have similar instruction sets.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/assembly-language-p02] Therefore, studying a single assembly language is sufficient to learn the basic concepts, recognize situations where the use of assembly language might be appropriate, and to see how efficient executable code can be created from high-level languages.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The **Commodore 64**, also known as the **C64**, is an 8-bit home computer introduced in January 1982 by Commodore International (first shown at the Consumer Electronics Show, January 7–10, 1982, in Las Vegas).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] It has been listed in the Guinness World Records as the best-selling desktop computer model of all time, with independent estimates placing the number sold between 12.5 and 17 million units.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Volume production started in early 1982, marketing in August for US$595 (equivalent to $1,990 in 2025).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Preceded by the VIC-20 and Commodore PET, the C64 took its name from its 64 kibibytes (65,536 bytes) of RAM.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] With support for multicolor sprites and a custom chip for waveform generation, the C64 could create superior visuals and audio compared to systems without such custom hardware.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The C64 dominated the low-end computer market (except in the UK, France and Japan, lasting only about six months in Japan) for most of the later years of the 1980s.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] For a substantial period (1983–1986), the C64 had between 30% and 40% share of the US market and two million units sold per year, outselling IBM PC compatibles, the Apple II, and Atari 8-bit computers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The Commodore 64 failed to make any impact in Japan, as their market was dominated by Japanese computers, such as the NEC PC-8801, Sharp X1, Fujitsu FM-7 and MSX, and in France, where the ZX Spectrum, Thomson MO5 and TO7, and Amstrad CPC 464 dominated the market.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Part of the Commodore 64's success was its sale in regular retail stores instead of only electronics or computer hobbyist specialty stores.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Commodore produced many of its parts in-house to control costs, including custom integrated circuit chips from MOS Technology.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In the United States, it has been compared to the Ford Model T automobile for its role in bringing a new technology to middle-class households via creative and affordable mass-production.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Approximately 10,000 commercial software titles have been made for the Commodore 64, including development tools, office productivity applications, and video games.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] C64 emulators allow anyone with a modern computer, or a compatible video game console, to run these programs today.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The C64 is also credited with popularizing the computer demoscene and is still used today by some computer hobbyists.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In 2011, 17 years after it was taken off the market, research showed that brand recognition for the model was still at 87%.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In January 1981, MOS Technology, Inc., Commodore's integrated circuit design subsidiary, initiated a project to design the graphic and audio chips for a next-generation video game console.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Design work for the chips, named MOS Technology VIC-II (Video Integrated Circuit for graphics) and MOS Technology SID (Sound Interface Device for audio), was completed in November 1981.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Commodore then began a game console project that would use the new chips—called the *Ultimax* or the *MAX Machine*, engineered by Yash Terakura from Commodore Japan.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] This project was eventually cancelled after just a few machines were manufactured for the Japanese market.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] At the same time, Robert "Bob" Russell (system programmer and architect on the VIC-20) and Robert "Bob" Yannes (engineer of the SID) were critical of the current product line-up at Commodore, which was a continuation of the Commodore PET line aimed at business users.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] With the support of Al Charpentier (engineer of the VIC-II) and Charles Winterble (manager of MOS Technology), they proposed to Commodore CEO Jack Tramiel a low-cost sequel to the VIC-20.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Tramiel dictated that the machine should have 64 KB of random-access memory (RAM).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Although 64-Kbit dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) chips cost over US$100 (equivalent to $299.35 in 2025) at the time, he knew that 64K DRAM prices were falling and would drop to an acceptable level before full production was reached.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The team was able to quickly design the computer because, unlike most other home-computer companies, Commodore had its own semiconductor fab to produce test chips; because the fab was not running at full capacity, development costs were part of existing corporate overhead.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The chips were complete by November, by which time Charpentier, Winterble, and Tramiel had decided to proceed with the new computer; the latter set a final deadline for the first weekend of January, to coincide with the 1982 Consumer Electronics Show (CES).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The product was code named the VIC-40 as the successor to the popular VIC-20.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The team that constructed it consisted of Yash Terakura, Shiraz Shivji, Bob Russell, Bob Yannes, and David A.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The design, prototypes, and some sample software were finished in time for the show, after the team had worked tirelessly over both Thanksgiving and Christmas weekends.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The machine used the same case, same-sized motherboard, and same Commodore BASIC 2.0 in ROM as the VIC-20.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] BASIC also served as the user interface shell and was available immediately on startup at the `READY` prompt.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] When the product was to be presented, the VIC-40 product was renamed C64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The C64 made an impressive debut at the January 1982 Consumer Electronics Show, as recalled by Production Engineer David A.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In July 1983, *BYTE* magazine stated that "the 64 retails for $595.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] *BYTE* gave more details, saying the C64 had "inadequate Commodore BASIC 2.0.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] *Creative Computing* said in December 1984 that the C64 was "the overwhelming winner" in the category of home computers under $500.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The Tandy Color Computer was the runner up.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The Apple II was the winner in the category of home computer over $500, which was the category the Commodore 64 was in when it was first released at the price of $595.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Commodore had a reputation for announcing products that never appeared, so the company sought to ship the C64 quickly.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Production began in the spring of 1982, and volume shipments began in August.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The C64 faced a wide range of competing home computers, but, with a lower price and more flexible hardware, it quickly outsold many of its competitors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In the United States, the greatest competitors were the Atari 8-bit computers, the Apple II, and the TI-99/4A.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The Atari 400 and 800 had been designed to accommodate previously stringent FCC emissions requirements and so were expensive to manufacture.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] However, the Apple II used its expansion slots for interfacing with common peripherals like disk drives, printers, and modems; the C64 had a variety of ports integrated into its motherboard, which were used for these purposes, usually leaving the cartridge port free.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Commodore's was not a completely closed system, however; the company had published detailed specifications for most of their models since the Commodore PET and VIC-20 days, and the C64 was no exception.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] This was in contrast to the TI-99/4A, as Texas Instruments focused less on hobbyists and more towards unsophisticated users.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] C64 sales were relatively slow due to a lack of software, reliability issues with early production models, particularly high failure rates of the PLA chip, which used a new production process, and a shortage of 1541 disk drives, which also suffered rather severe reliability issues.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] During 1983, however, a trickle of software turned into a flood and sales began rapidly climbing.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Commodore sold the C64 not only through its network of authorized dealers but also through department stores, discount stores, toy stores and college bookstores.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The C64 had a built-in RF modulator and thus could be plugged into any television set.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] This allowed it (like its predecessor, the VIC-20) to compete directly against video game consoles such as the Atari 2600.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Like the Apple IIe, the C64 could also output a composite video signal, avoiding the RF modulator altogether.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] This allowed the C64 to be plugged into a specialized monitor for a sharper picture.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Unlike the IIe, the C64's NTSC output capability also included separate luminance/chroma signal output equivalent to (and electrically compatible with) S-Video, for connection to the Commodore 1702 monitor, providing even better video quality than a composite signal.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Aggressive pricing of the C64 is considered to have been a major catalyst in the video game crash of 1983.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In January 1983, Commodore announced the first suggest price drop from $595 down to $425.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In April 1983, Commodore offered a $100 rebate in the United States on the purchase of a C64 to anyone that traded in another video game console or computer, bringing the effective price down to $299.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] To take advantage of this rebate, some mail-order dealers and retailers offered a Timex Sinclair 1000 (TS1000) for as little as $10 with the purchase of a C64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] This deal meant that the consumer could send the TS1000 to Commodore, collect the rebate, and pocket the difference; Timex Corporation departed the computer market within a year.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Commodore's tactics soon led to a price war with the major home computer manufacturers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The success of the VIC-20 and C64 contributed significantly to Texas Instruments and other smaller competitors exiting the field.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The price war with Texas Instruments was seen as a personal battle for Commodore president Jack Tramiel.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Commodore dropped the C64's list price by $200 within two months of its release.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In June 1983 the company lowered the price to $300 (equivalent to $1000 in 2025), and some stores sold the computer for $199.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] At one point, the company was selling as many C64s as all computers sold by the rest of the industry combined.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Meanwhile, TI lost money by selling the TI-99/4A for $99.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] TI's subsequent demise in the home computer industry in October 1983 was seen as revenge for TI's tactics in the electronic calculator market in the mid-1970s, when Commodore was almost bankrupted by TI.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] All four machines had similar memory configurations which were standard in 1982–83: 48 KB for the Apple II+ (upgraded within months of C64's release to 64 KB with the Apple IIe) and 48 KB for the Atari 800.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] At upwards of $1,200, the Apple II was about twice as expensive, while the Atari 800 cost $899.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] One key to the C64's success was Commodore's aggressive marketing tactics, and they were quick to exploit the relative price/performance divisions between its competitors with a series of television commercials after the C64's launch in late 1982.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The company also published detailed documentation to help developers, while Atari initially kept technical information secret.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Although many early C64 games were inferior Atari 8-bit ports, by late 1983, the growing installed base caused developers to create new software with better graphics and sound.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] With sales booming and the early reliability issues with the hardware addressed, software for the C64 began to grow in size and ambition during 1984.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] This growth shifted to the primary focus of most US game developers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The two holdouts were Sierra, who largely skipped over the C64 in favor of Apple and PC-compatible machines, and Broderbund, who were heavily invested in educational software and developed primarily around the Apple II.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In the North American market, the disk format had become nearly universal while cassette and cartridge-based software all but disappeared.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Most US-developed games by this point grew large enough to require multi-loading from disk.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] At a mid-1984 conference of game developers and experts at Origins Game Fair, Dan Bunten, Sid Meier, and a representative of Avalon Hill said that they were developing games for the C64 first as the most promising market.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] By 1985, games were an estimated 60 to 70% of Commodore 64 software.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] *Computer Gaming World* stated in January 1985 that companies such as Epyx that survived the video game crash did so because they "jumped on the Commodore bandwagon early".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Over 35% of SSI's 1986 sales were for the C64, ten points higher than for the Apple II.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The C64 was even more important for other companies, which often found that more than half the sales for a title ported to six platforms came from the C64 version.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In Europe, the primary competitors to the C64 were British-built computers: the Sinclair ZX Spectrum, the BBC Micro, and the Amstrad CPC 464.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In the UK, the 48K Spectrum had not only been released a few months ahead of the C64's early 1983 debut, but it was also selling for £175, less than half the C64's £399 price.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The Spectrum quickly became the market leader and Commodore had an uphill struggle against it in the marketplace.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The C64 did however go on to rival the Spectrum in popularity in the latter half of the 1980s.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Adjusted to the population size, the popularity of Commodore 64 was the highest in Finland at roughly 3 units per 100 inhabitants, where it was subsequently marketed as "the Computer of the Republic".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] By early 1985 the C64's price was $149; with an estimated production cost of $35–50, its profitability was still within the industry-standard markup of two to three times.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Commodore sold about one million C64s in 1985 and a total of 3.5 million by mid-1986.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Although the company reportedly attempted to discontinue the C64 more than once in favor of more expensive computers such as the Commodore 128, demand remained strong.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In 1986, Commodore introduced the 64C, a redesigned 64, which *Compute!* saw as evidence that—contrary to C64 owners' fears that the company would abandon them in favor of the Amiga and 128—"the 64 refuses to die".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Its introduction also meant that Commodore raised the price of the C64 for the first time, which the magazine cited as the end of the home-computer price war.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Software sales also remained strong; MicroProse, for example, in 1987 cited the Commodore and IBM PC markets as its top priorities.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] By 1988, PC compatibles were the largest and fastest-growing home and entertainment software markets, displacing former leader Commodore.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Software sales for Apple II and Atari 8-bit decreased, but sales for the 64 remained strong, albeit almost unchanged in the third quarter of 1988 year over year, while the overall market grew 42% driven by PC games.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Commodore was still selling 1 to 1.5 million 64 units worldwide each year of what *Computer Chronicles* that year called "the Model T of personal computers".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Epyx CEO Dave Morse cautioned that "there are no new 64 buyers, or very few.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Trip Hawkins reinforced that sentiment, stating that Nintendo was "the last hurrah of the 8-bit world".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] SSI exited the Commodore 64 market in 1991, after most competitors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] *Ultima VI*, released in 1991, was the last major C64 game release from a North American developer, and *The Simpsons*, published by Ultra Games, was the last arcade conversion.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In the European market, disk software was rarer and cassettes were the most common distribution method; this led to a higher prevalence of arcade titles and smaller, lower-budget games that could fit entirely in the computer's memory without requiring multiloads.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] European programmers also tended to exploit advanced features of the C64's hardware more than their US counterparts.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The Commodore 64 Light Fantastic pack was released in time for the 1989 Christmas holiday season.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The package included a C64C, a Cheetah Defender 64 Light gun and 3D-glasses.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In the United States, demand for 8-bit computers all but ceased as the 1990s began and PC compatibles completely dominated the computer market.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] However, the C64 continued to be popular in the UK and other European countries.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The machine's eventual demise was not due to lack of demand or the cost of the C64 itself (still profitable at a retail price point between £44 and £50), but rather because of the cost of producing the disk drive.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In March 1994, at CeBIT in Hanover, Germany, Commodore announced that the C64 would be finally discontinued in 1995, noting that the Commodore 1541 cost more than the C64 itself.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] However, only one month later in April 1994, the company filed for bankruptcy.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] When Commodore went bankrupt, all production on their inventory, including the C64, was discontinued, thus ending the C64's 11+1⁄2-year production.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Claims of sales of 17, 22 and 30 million of C64 units sold worldwide have been made.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Company sales records, however, indicate that the total number was about 12.5 million.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Based on that figure, the Commodore 64 was still the third most popular computing platform into the 21st century until 2017 when the Raspberry Pi family replaced it.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] While 360,000 C64s were sold in 1982, about 1.3 million were sold in 1983, followed by a large spike in 1984 when 2.6 million were sold.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] After that, sales held steady at between 1.3 and 1.6 million a year for the remainder of the decade and then dropped off after 1989.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] North American sales peaked between 1983 and 1985 and gradually tapered off afterward, while European sales remained quite strong into the early 1990s.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Commodore itself reported a robust sales figure of over 800,000 units during the 1991 fiscal year, but sales during the 1993 fiscal year had declined to fewer than 200,000 units.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Throughout the early 1990s, European sales had accounted for more than 80% of Commodore's total sales revenue.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] On June 7, 2025, YouTuber Christian Simpson of the channel Retro Recipes (later renamed to Retro Recipes x Commodore) released the video titled "Can We Save The COMMODORE Brand?
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] My Biggest Project Yet", at the end of which he hinted at acquiring the entire holding company maintaining the original Commodore trademarks and branding (Commodore Corporation B.V.).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] On June 28, 2025, a follow up video was released which announced that an agreement had been reached and hinted at an upcoming hardware release.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The system was created with community partners and their projects such as Gideon Zweijtzer (of Gideon's Logic) and a customized variant of the Ultimate64 Elite-II mainboard.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The base model re-release features a breadbin styled case and keyboard with classic coloring, while other editions offer RGB lighting and transparent / semi-transparent cases.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The original schedule called for units to be shipped in October or November 2025.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] As of January 2026, the Commodore 64 Ultimate had been released to reviewers, with units due to ship in March 2026.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In 1982, Commodore released the MAX Machine in Japan.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] It was called the Ultimax in the United States and VC-10 in Germany.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The MAX was intended to be a game console with limited computing capability and was based on a cut-down version of the hardware family later used in the C64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The MAX was discontinued months after its introduction because of poor sales in Japan.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] 1983 saw Commodore attempt to compete with the Apple II's hold on the US education market with the Educator 64, essentially a C64 and "green" monochrome monitor in a PET case.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Schools preferred the all-in-one metal construction of the PET over the standard C64's separate components, which could be easily damaged, vandalized, or stolen.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Schools did not prefer the Educator 64 to the wide range of software and hardware options the Apple IIe was able to offer, and it was produced in limited quantities.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Also in 1983, Commodore released the SX-64, a portable version of the C64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The SX-64 has the distinction of being the first commercial *full-color* portable computer.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] While earlier computers using this form factor only incorporate monochrome ("green screen") displays, the base SX-64 unit features a 5 in (130 mm) color cathode ray tube (CRT) and one integrated 1541 floppy disk drive.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Even though Commodore claimed in advertisements that it would have dual 1541 drives, when the SX-64 was released there was only one and the other became a floppy disk storage slot.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Also, unlike most other C64s, the SX-64 does not have a datasette connector so an external cassette was not an option.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Two designers at Commodore, Fred Bowen and Bil Herd, were determined to rectify the problems of the Plus/4.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] They intended that the eventual successors to the C64—the Commodore 128 and 128D computers (1985)—were to build upon the C64, avoiding the Plus/4's flaws.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The successors had many improvements such as a BASIC with graphics and sound commands (like almost all home computers not made by Commodore), 80-column display ability, and full CP/M compatibility.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The decision to make the Commodore 128 plug compatible with the C64 was made quietly by Bowen and Herd, software and hardware designers respectively, without the knowledge or approval by the management in the post Jack Tramiel era.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The designers were careful not to reveal their decision until the project was too far along to be challenged or changed and still make the impending Consumer Electronics Show (CES) in Las Vegas.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Upon learning that the C128 was designed to be compatible with the C64, Commodore's marketing department independently announced that the C128 would be 100% compatible with the C64, thereby raising the bar for C64 support.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In a case of malicious compliance, the 128 design was altered to include a separate "64 mode" using a complete C64 environment to try to ensure total compatibility.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The C64's designers intended the computer to have a new, wedge-shaped case within a year of release, but the change did not occur.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In 1986, Commodore released the 64C computer, which is functionally identical to the original, which was nicknamed the Breadbin 64 after the release of the 64C.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The exterior design was remodeled in the sleeker style of the Commodore 128.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The 64C uses new versions of the SID, VIC-II, and I/O chips being deployed.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Models with the C64E board had the graphic symbols printed on the top of the keys, instead of the normal location on the front.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The sound chip (SID) was changed to use the MOS 8580 chip, with the core voltage reduced from 12V to 9V.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The 64 KiB RAM memory went from eight chips to two chips.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] BASIC and the KERNAL went from two separate chips into one 16 KiB ROM chip.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The PLA chip and some TTL chips were integrated into a DIL 64-pin chip.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The "252535-01" PLA integrated the color RAM as well into the same chip.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The smaller physical space made it impossible to put in some internal expansions like a floppy-speeder.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In the United States, the 64C was often bundled with the third-party GEOS graphical user interface (GUI)-based operating system, as well as the software needed to access Quantum Link.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The 1541 drive received a matching face-lift, resulting in the 1541C.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Later, a smaller, sleeker 1541-II model was introduced, along with the 800 KB 3.5-inch microfloppy 1581.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In 1990, the C64 was repackaged in the form of a game console, called the C64 Games System (C64GS), with most external connectivity removed.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] A simple modification to the 64C's motherboard was made to allow cartridges to be inserted from above.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] A modified ROM replaced the BASIC interpreter with a boot screen to inform the user to insert a cartridge.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Designed to compete with the Nintendo Entertainment System and Sega's Master System, it suffered from very low sales compared to its rivals.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] It was another commercial failure for Commodore, and it was never released outside Europe.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The Commodore game system lacked a keyboard, so any software that required a keyboard could not be used.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In 1990, an advanced successor to the C64, the Commodore 65 (also known as the "C64DX"), was prototyped, but the project was canceled by Commodore's chairman Irving Gould in 1991.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The C65's specifications were impressive for an 8-bit computer, bringing specs comparable to the 16-bit Apple IIGS.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] For example, it could display 256 colors on the screen, while OCS based Amigas could only display 64 in HalfBrite mode (32 colors and half-bright transformations).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Although no specific reason was given for the C65's cancellation, it would have competed in the marketplace with Commodore's lower-end Amigas and the Commodore CDTV.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] In 1982, the C64's graphics and sound capabilities were rivaled only by the Atari 8-bit computers and appeared exceptional when compared with the popular Apple II.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The C64 is often credited with starting the demoscene subculture (see Commodore 64 demos).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] It is still being actively used in the demoscene, especially for music (its SID sound chip even being used in special sound cards for PCs, and the Elektron SidStation synthesizer).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Even though other computers quickly caught up with it, the C64 remained a strong competitor to the later video game consoles Nintendo Entertainment System (NES) and Master System, thanks in part to its by-then established software base.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Because of lower incomes and the domination of the ZX Spectrum in the UK, almost all British C64 software used cassette tapes.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Few cassette C64 programs were released in the US after 1983 and, in North America, the diskette was the principal method of software distribution.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The cartridge slot on the C64 was also mainly a feature used in the computer's first two years on the US market and became rapidly obsolete once the price and reliability of 1541 drives improved.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] A handful of PAL region games used bank switched cartridges to get around the 16 KiB memory limit.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] As is common for home computers of the early 1980s, the C64 comes with a BASIC interpreter, in ROM.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] KERNAL, I/O, and tape/disk drive operations are accessed via custom BASIC language commands.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The disk drive has its own interfacing microprocessor and ROM (firmware) I/O routines, much like the earlier CBM/PET systems and the Atari 400 and Atari 800.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] This means that no memory space is dedicated to running a disk operating system, as was the case with earlier systems such as the Apple II and TRS-80.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Commodore BASIC 2.0 is used instead of the more advanced BASIC 4.0 from the PET series, since C64 users were not expected to need the disk-oriented enhancements of BASIC 4.0.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The company did not expect many to buy a disk drive, and using BASIC 2.0 simplified VIC-20 owners' transition to the 64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] "The choice of BASIC 2.0 instead of 4.0 was made with some soul-searching, not just at random.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The typical user of a C64 is not expected to need the direct disk commands as much as other extensions, and the amount of memory to be committed to BASIC were to be limited.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] We chose to leave expansion space for color and sound extensions instead of the disk features.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The version of Microsoft BASIC is not very comprehensive and does not include specific commands for sound or graphics manipulation, instead requiring users to use the "PEEK and POKE" commands to access the graphics and sound chip registers directly.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] To provide extended commands, including graphics and sound, Commodore produced two different cartridge-based extensions to BASIC 2.0: Simons' BASIC and Super Expander 64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Other languages available for the C64 include Pascal, C, Logo, Forth, and FORTRAN.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Compilers for BASIC 2.0 such as Petspeed 2 (from Commodore), Blitz (from Jason Ranheim), and Turbo Lightning (from Ocean Software) were produced.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Most commercial C64 software was written in assembly language, either cross-developed on a larger computer, or directly on the C64 using a machine code monitor or an assembler.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] This maximized speed and minimized memory use.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Some games, particularly adventures, used high-level scripting languages and sometimes mixed BASIC and machine language.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Many third-party operating systems have been developed for the C64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] As well as the original GEOS, two third-party GEOS-compatible systems have been written: Wheels and GEOS megapatch.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Both of these require hardware upgrades to the original C64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Several other operating systems are or have been available, including WiNGS OS, the Unix-like LUnix, operated from a command-line, and the embedded systems OS Contiki, with full GUI.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Other less well-known OSes include ACE, Asterix, DOS/65, and GeckOS.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] C64 OS, albeit not a full operating system, is commercially available today and remains under active development.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] It features a full GUI in character mode, and many other modern features.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] A version of CP/M was released, but this requires the addition of an external Z80 processor to the expansion bus.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Furthermore, the Z80 processor is underclocked to be compatible with the C64's memory bus, so performance is poor compared to other CP/M implementations.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] C64 CP/M and C128 CP/M both suffer a lack of software; although most commercial CP/M software can run on these systems, software media is incompatible between platforms.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The low usage of CP/M on Commodores means that software houses saw no need to invest in mastering versions for the Commodore disk format.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The C64 CP/M cartridge is also not compatible with anything except the early 326298 motherboards.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] During the 1980s, the Commodore 64 was used to run bulletin board systems using software packages such as Punter BBS, Bizarre 64, Blue Board, C-Net, Color 64, CMBBS, C-Base, DMBBS, Image BBS, EBBS, and The Deadlock Deluxe BBS Construction Kit, often with sysop-made modifications.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] These boards sometimes were used to distribute cracked software.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] As late as December 2013, there were 25 such Bulletin Board Systems in operation, reachable via the Telnet protocol.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] There were major commercial online services, such as Compunet (UK), CompuServe (US – later bought by America Online), The Source (US), and Minitel (France) among many others.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] These services usually required custom software which was often bundled with a modem and included free online time as they were billed by the minute.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Quantum Link (or Q-Link) was a US and Canadian online service for Commodore 64 and 128 personal computers that operated from November 5, 1985, to November 1, 1994.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] It was operated by Quantum Computer Services of Vienna, Virginia, which in October 1991 changed its name to America Online and continued to operate its AOL service for the IBM PC compatible and Apple Macintosh.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Q-Link was a modified version of the PlayNET system, which Control Video Corporation (CVC, later renamed Quantum Computer Services) licensed.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] The first graphical character-based interactive environment is *Club Caribe*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] First released as *Habitat* in 1988, *Club Caribe* was introduced by LucasArts for Q-Link customers on their Commodore 64 computers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Users could interact with one another, chat and exchange items.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Although the game's open world was very basic, its use of online avatars and the combination of chat and graphics was revolutionary.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Online graphics in the late 1980s were severely restricted by the need to support modem data transfer rates as low as 300 bits per second.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p01] Habitat's graphics were stored locally on floppy disk, eliminating the need for network transfer.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The C64 uses an 8-bit MOS Technology 6510 microprocessor that is almost identical to the 6502 but has three-state buses, a different pinout, slightly different clock signals and other minor changes for this application.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] It also has six I/O lines on otherwise-unused legs on the 40-pin IC package.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] These are used for two purposes in the C64: to bank-switch the machine's read-only memory (ROM) in and out of the processor's address space, and to operate the datasette tape recorder.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The C64 has 64 KB of 8-bit-wide dynamic RAM, 1 KB of 4-bit-wide static color RAM for text mode, and 38 KB are available to built-in Commodore BASIC 2.0 on startup.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] There is 20 KB of ROM, made up of the BASIC interpreter, the KERNAL, and the character ROM.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Because the processor can only address 64 KB at a time, the ROM was mapped into memory and only 38911 bytes of RAM (plus 4 KB between the ROMs) were available at startup.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Most "breadbin" Commodore 64s used 4164 DRAM with eight chips totaling 64K of system RAM.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Later models, featuring Assy 250466 and Assy 250469 motherboards, used 41464 DRAM (64K×4) chips which stored 32 KB per chip (so only two were required).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Because 4164 DRAMs are 64K×1, eight chips are needed to make an entire byte; the computer will not function without all of them present.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The first chip contains Bit 0 for the memory space, the second chip contains Bit 1, and so forth.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The C64 performs a RAM test on power-up and if a RAM error is detected, the amount of free BASIC memory will be lower than the normal 38,911.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] If the faulty chip is in lower memory, then an `?OUT OF MEMORY IN 0` error is displayed rather than the usual BASIC startup banner.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The C64 uses a complicated memory-banking scheme; the normal power-on default is the BASIC ROM mapped in at $A000–$BFFF, and the screen editor (KERNAL) ROM at $E000–$FFFF.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] RAM under the system ROMs can be written to, but not read back, without swapping out the ROMs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Memory location $01 contains a register with control bits for enabling or disabling the system ROMs and the I/O area at $D000.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] If the KERNAL ROM is swapped out, BASIC will be removed at the same time.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] BASIC is not active without the KERNAL; BASIC often calls KERNAL routines, and part of the ROM code for BASIC is in the KERNAL ROM.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The character ROM is normally invisible to the CPU.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The character ROM may be mapped into $D000–$DFFF, where it is then visible to the CPU.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Because doing so necessitates swapping out the I/O registers, interrupts must first be disabled.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] By removing I/O from the memory map, $D000–$DFFF becomes free RAM.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] C64 cartridges map into assigned ranges in the CPU's address space.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The most common cartridge auto-starting requires a string at $8000 which contains "CBM80" followed by the address where program execution begins.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] A few C64 cartridges released in 1982 use Ultimax mode (or MAX mode), a leftover feature of the unsuccessful MAX Machine.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] These cartridges map into $F000 and displace the KERNAL ROM.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] If Ultimax mode is used, the programmer will have to provide code for handling system interrupts.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The cartridge port has 16 address lines, which grants access to the computer's entire address space if needed.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Disk and tape software normally load at the start of BASIC memory ($0801), and use a small BASIC stub (such as `10 SYS(2064)`) to jump to the start of the program.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Although no Commodore 8-bit machine except the C128 can automatically boot from a floppy disk, some software intentionally overwrites certain BASIC vectors in the process of loading so execution begins automatically (instead of requiring the user to type RUN at the BASIC prompt after loading).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] About 300 cartridges were released for the C64, primarily during the machine's first 2+1⁄2 years on the market, after which most software outgrew the 16 KB cartridge limit.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] One notable third-party expansion was the Power Cartridge, developed by Dutch company Kolff Computer Supplies (KCS).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] It provided a BASIC extension toolkit, a machine code monitor, a reset button, and fastload routines that accelerated cassette and disk access (up to 10× and 6× respectively).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Popular in the Benelux region, it was used for both productivity and programming purposes.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Larger software companies, such as Ocean Software, began releasing games on bank-switched cartridges to overcome the 16 KB cartridge limit during the C64's final years.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Commodore did not include a reset button on its computers until the CBM-II line, but third-party cartridges had a reset button.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] A soft reset can be triggered by jumping to the CPU reset routine at $FCE2 (64738).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] A few programs use this as an exit feature, although it does not clear memory.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The KERNAL ROM underwent three revisions, mainly designed to fix bugs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The initial version is only found on 326298 motherboards (used in the first production models), and cannot detect whether an NTSC or PAL VIC-II is present.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The second revision is found on all C64s made from late 1982 through 1985.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The final KERNAL ROM revision was introduced on the 250466 motherboard (late breadbin models with 41464 RAM), and is found in all C64Cs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The 6510 CPU is clocked at 1.023 MHz (NTSC) and 0.985 MHz (PAL), lower than some competing systems; the Atari 800, for example, is clocked at 1.79 MHz).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Performance can be boosted slightly by disabling the VIC-II's video output via a register write.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] This feature is often used by tape and disk fast loaders and the KERNAL cassette routine to keep a standard CPU cycle timing not modified by the VIC-II's sharing of the bus.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The restore key is gated directly to the CPU's NMI line, and will generate an NMI if pressed.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The KERNAL handler for the NMI checks if run/stop is also pressed; if not, it ignores the NMI and exits.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Run/stop-restore is normally a soft reset in BASIC which restores all I/O registers to their power-on default state, but does not clear memory or reset pointers; any BASIC programs in memory will be left untouched.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Machine-language software usually disables run/stop-restore by remapping the NMI vector to a dummy RTI instruction.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The NMI can also be used for an extra interrupt thread by programs, but risks a system lockup or other undesirable side effects if the restore key is accidentally pressed (which activates the NMI thread).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The C64 retained the VIC-20's DE-9 Atari joystick port and added another; any Atari-specification game controller can be used on a C64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The joysticks are read from the registers at $DC00 and $DC01, and most software is designed to use a joystick in port 2 for control rather than port 1; the upper bits of $DC00 are used by the keyboard, and an I/O conflict can result.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Although it is possible to use Sega gamepads on a C64, it is not recommended; their slightly different signal can damage the CIA chip.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The SID chip's register $D419, used to control paddles, is an analog input.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] A handful of games, primarily released early in the computer's life cycle, can use paddles.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] In 1986, Commodore released two mice for the C64 and C128: the 1350 and 1351.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The 1350 is a digital device read from the joystick registers, and can be used with any program supporting joystick input.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The 1351 is an analog potentiometer-based mouse, read with the SID's analog-to-digital converter.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The VIC-II graphics chip features a new palette, eight hardware sprites per scanline (enabling up to 112 sprites per PAL screen), scrolling capabilities, and two bitmap graphics modes.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The standard text mode features 40 columns, like most Commodore PET models; the built-in character encoding is not standard ASCII but PETSCII, an extended form of ASCII-1963.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The KERNAL ROM sets the VIC-II to a dark-blue background on power-up, with a light-blue border and text.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Unlike the PET and VIC-20, the C64 uses double-width text; some early VIC-IIs had poor video quality which resulted in a fuzzy picture.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Most screenshots show borders around the screen, a feature of the VIC-II chip.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] By utilizing interrupts to reset hardware registers with precise timing, it was possible to place graphics within the borders and use the full screen.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The C64 has a resolution of 320×200 pixels, consisting of a 40×25 grid of 8×8 character blocks.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] It has 256 predefined character blocks, known as PETSCII.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The character set can be copied into RAM and modified by a programmer.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] In multicolor mode, attributes are shared between pixel pairs so the effective visible resolution is 160×200 pixels; only 16 KiB of memory is available for the VIC-II video processor.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Since the C64 has a bitmapped screen, it is possible (but slow) to draw each pixel individually.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Most programmers used techniques developed for earlier, non-bitmapped systems like the Commodore PET and TRS-80.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] A programmer redraws the character set, and the video processor fills the screen block by block from the top left corner to the bottom right corner.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Two types of animation are used: character block animation and hardware sprites.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The user draws a series of characters of a person walking, possibly two in the middle of the block and another two walking in and out of the block.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Then the user sequences them so the character walks into the block and out again.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Drawing a series of these gets a person walking across the screen.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] By timing the redraw to occur when the television screen blanks out to restart drawing the screen, there will be no flicker.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] For this to happen, a user programs the VIC-II that it generates a raster interrupt when video flyback occurs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] This technique is used in the *Space Invaders* arcade game.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Horizontal and vertical pixel scrolling of up to one character block is supported by two hardware scroll registers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Depending on timing, hardware scrolling affects the entire screen or selected lines of character blocks.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] On a non-emulated C64, scrolling is glass-like and blur-free.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] A sprite is a character which moves over an area of the screen, draws over the background, and redraws it after it moves.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] This differs from character block animation, where the user flips character blocks.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] On the C64, the VIC-II video controller handles most sprite emulation; the programmer defines the sprite and where it goes.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The C64 has two types of sprites, respecting their color-mode limitations.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Hi-res sprites have one color (one background and one foreground), and multi-color sprites have three (one background and three foreground).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Color modes can be split or windowed on a single screen.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Sprites can be doubled in size vertically and horizontally up to four times their size, but the pixel attributes are the same – the pixels become "fatter".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] There are eight sprites, and all eight can be shown in each horizontal line concurrently.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Sprites can move with glassy smoothness in front of, and behind, screen characters and other sprites.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The hardware sprites of a C64 can be displayed on a bitmapped (high-resolution) screen or a text-mode screen in conjunction with fast and smooth character block animation.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Software-emulated sprites on systems without support for hardware sprites, such as the Apple II and ZX Spectrum, required a bitmapped screen.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Sprite-sprite and sprite-background collisions are detected in hardware, and the VIC-II can be programmed to trigger an interrupt accordingly.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The SID chip has three channels, each with its own ADSR envelope generator and filter capabilities.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Ring modulation makes use of channel three to work with the other two channels.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Bob Yannes developed the SID chip and, later, co-founded the synthesizer company Ensoniq.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Composers and programmers of game music on the C64 include Rob Hubbard, Jeroen Tel, Tim Follin, David Whittaker, Chris Hülsbeck, Ben Daglish, Martin Galway, Kjell Nordbø and David Dunn.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Due to the chip's three channels, chords are often played as arpeggios.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] It was also possible to continuously update the master volume with sampled data to enable the playback of 4-bit digitized audio.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] By 2008, it was possible to play four-channel 8-bit audio samples and two SID channels and still use filtering.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] There are two versions of the SID chip: the 6581 and the 8580.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The MOS Technology 6581 was used in the original ("breadbin") C64s, the early versions of the 64C, and the Commodore 128.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The 6581 was replaced with the MOS Technology 8580 in 1987.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Although the 6581 sound quality is a little crisper, it lacks the 8580's versatility; the 8580 can mix all available waveforms on each channel, but the 6581 can only mix waveforms in a channel in a limited fashion.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The main difference between the 6581 and the 8580 is the supply voltage; the 6581 requires 12 volts, and the 8580 9 volts.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] A modification can be made to use the 6581 in a newer 64C board (which uses the 9-volt chip).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] In 1986, the Sound Expander was released for the Commodore 64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] It was a sound module with a Yamaha YM3526 chip capable of FM synthesis, primarily intended for professional music production.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Commodore made many changes to the C64's hardware, sometimes introducing compatibility issues.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Cost reduction was the reason for most of the revisions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Reducing manufacturing costs was vitally important to Commodore's survival during the price war and lean years of the 16-bit era.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The C64's original (NMOS-based) motherboard went through two major redesigns and a number of revisions, exchanging positions of the VIC-II, SID and PLA chips.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Much of the cost was initially eliminated by reducing the number of discrete components, such as diodes and resistors, which enabled a smaller printed circuit board.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] There were 16 C64 motherboard revisions to simplify production and reduce manufacturing costs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Some board revisions were exclusive to PAL regions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] All C64 motherboards were manufactured in Hong Kong.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] IC locations changed frequently with each motherboard revision, as did the presence (or lack) of the metal RF shield around the VIC-II; PAL boards often had aluminized cardboard instead of a metal shield.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The SID and VIC-II are socketed on all boards, but the other ICs may be socketed or soldered.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The first production C64s, made from 1982 to early 1983, are known as "silver label" models due to the case having a silver-colored "Commodore" logo.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The power LED had a silver badge reading "64" around it.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] These machines have only a five-pin video cable, and cannot produce S-Video.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Commodore introduced the familiar "rainbow badge" case in late 1982, but many machines produced into early 1983 also used silver-label cases until the existing stock was used up.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The original 326298 board was replaced in spring 1983 by the 250407 motherboard, which had an eight-pin video connector and added S-Video support.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] This case design was used until the C64C appeared in 1986.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] All ICs switched to plastic shells, but the silver-label C64s (notably the VIC-II) had some ceramic ICs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The case is made from ABS plastic, which may become brown with time; this can be reversed with retrobright.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The VIC-II was manufactured with 5-micrometer NMOS technology, and was clocked at 17.73447 MHz (PAL) or 14.31818 MHz (NTSC).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Internally, the clock was divided to generate the dot clock (about 8 MHz) and the two-phase system clocks (about 1 MHz; the pixel and system clock speeds differ slightly on NTSC and PAL machines).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] At such high clock rates the chip generated considerable heat, forcing MOS Technology to use a ceramic dual in-line package known as a CERDIP.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The ceramic package was more expensive, but dissipated heat more effectively than plastic.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] After a redesign in 1983, the VIC-II was encased in a plastic dual in-line package; this reduced costs substantially, but did not eliminate the heat problem.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Without a ceramic package, the VIC-II required a heat sink.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] To avoid extra cost, the metal RF shielding doubled as the VIC's heat sink; not all units shipped with this type of shielding, however.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Most C64s in Europe shipped with a cardboard RF shield coated with a layer of metal foil.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The effectiveness of the cardboard was questionable; it acted instead as an insulator, blocking airflow and trapping heat generated by the SID, VIC, and PLA chips.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The SID was originally manufactured using NMOS at 7 micrometers and, in some areas, 6 micrometers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The prototype SID and some early production models had a ceramic dual in-line package, but (unlike the VIC-II) are very rare; the SID was encased in plastic when production began in early 1982.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] In 1986, Commodore released the last revision of the classic C64 motherboard.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] It was otherwise identical to the 1984 design, except for two 64-kilobit × 4-bit DRAM chips which replaced the original eight 64-kilobit × 1-bit ICs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] After the release of the Commodore 64C, MOS Technology began to reconfigure the original C64's chipset to use HMOS technology.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The main benefit of HMOS was that it required less voltage to drive the IC, generating less heat.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] This enhanced the reliability of the SID and VIC-II.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The new chipset was renumbered 85xx to reflect the change to HMOS.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] In 1987, Commodore released a 64C variant with a redesigned motherboard known as a "short board".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The new board used the HMOS chipset, with a new 64-pin PLA chip.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The "SuperPLA", as it was called, integrated discrete components and transistor–transistor logic (TTL) chips.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] In the last revision of the 64C motherboard, the 2114 4-bit-wide color RAM was integrated into the SuperPLA.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The C64 used an external power supply, a linear transformer with multiple taps differing from switch mode (presently used on PC power supplies).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] It was encased in epoxy resin gel, which discouraged tampering but increased the heat level during use.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The design saved space in the computer's case, and allowed international versions to be more easily manufactured.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The 1541-II and 1581 disk drives and third-party clones also have external power-supply "bricks", like most peripherals.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Commodore power supplies often failed sooner than expected.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The computer reportedly had a 30-percent return rate in late 1983, compared to the 5–7 percent rate considered acceptable by the industry; *Creative Computing* reported four working C64s, out of seven.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Malfunctioning power bricks were notorious for damaging the RAM chips.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Due to their higher density and single supply (+5V), they had less tolerance for over-voltage.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The usually-failing voltage regulator could be replaced by piggybacking a new regulator on the board and fitting a heat sink on top.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The original PSU on early-1982 and 1983 machines had a 5-pin connector which could accidentally be plugged into the computer's video output.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Commodore later changed the design, omitting the resin gel to reduce costs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The following model, the Commodore 128, used a larger, improved power supply which included a fuse.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The power supply for the Commodore REU was similar to that of the Commodore 128, providing an upgrade for customers purchasing the accessory.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Creative Micro Designs also produced a 2 MB REU for the C64 and C128, called the 1750 XL.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The technology actually supported up to 16 MB, but 2 MB was the biggest one officially made.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Expansions of up to 16 MB were also possible via the CMD SuperCPU.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The 9 volt AC is used to supply power via a charge pump to the SID sound generator chip, provide 6.8 V via a rectifier to the cassette motor, a "0" pulse for every positive half wave to the time-of-day (TOD) input on the CIA chips, and 9 volts AC directly to the user-port.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Thus, as a minimum, a 12 V square wave is required.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Note that even if an I/O chip like the VIC-II only uses 64 positions in the memory address space, it will occupy 1,024 addresses because some address bits are left undecoded.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Vertical integration was the key to keeping Commodore 64 production costs low.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] At the introduction in 1982, the production cost was US$135 and the retail price US$595.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] In 1985, the retail price went down to US$149 (US$450 today) and the production costs were believed to be somewhere between US$35–50 (c.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Commodore would not confirm this cost figure.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Dougherty of the Berkeley Softworks estimated the costs of the Commodore 64 parts based on his experience at Mattel and Imagic.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] To lower costs, TTL chips were replaced with less expensive custom chips and ways to increase the yields on the sound and graphics chips were found.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The video chip 6567 had the ceramic package replaced with plastic but heat dissipation demanded a redesign of the chip and the development of a plastic package that can dissipate heat as well as ceramic.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] C64 enthusiasts were developing new hardware in 2008, including Ethernet cards, specially adapted hard disks and flash card interfaces (sd2iec).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] A-SID, which gives the C-64 a wah-wah effect, was introduced in 2022.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] C64 clones are computers which imitate Commodore 64 functions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] In mid-2004, after an absence from the marketplace of more than 10 years, PC manufacturer Tulip Computers (owners of the Commodore brand since 1997) announced the C64 Direct-to-TV (C64DTV): a joystick-based TV game based on the C64, with 30 games in its ROM.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Designed by Jeri Ellsworth, a self-taught computer designer who had designed the C-One C64 implementation, the C64DTV was similar to other mini-consoles based on the modestly-successful Atari 2600 and Intellivision.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The C64DTV was advertised on QVC in the United States for the 2004 holiday season.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] In 2015, a Commodore 64-compatible motherboard was produced by Individual Computers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Called the C64 Reloaded, it is a redesign of Commodore 64 motherboard revision 250466 with several new features.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The motherboard is designed to be placed in an existing, empty C64 or C64C case.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Produced in limited quantities, models of this Commodore 64 clone have machined or ZIF sockets in which custom C64 chips are placed.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The board contains jumpers to accept revisions of the VIC-II and SID chips and the ability to switch between the PAL and NTSC video systems.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] It has several innovations, including selection (via the restore key) of KERNAL and character ROMs, built-in reset toggle on the power switch, and an S-Video socket to replace the original TV modulator.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The motherboard is powered by a DC-to-DC converter which uses 12 V DC from a mains adapter, rather than the original (and failure-prone) Commodore 64 power-supply brick.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The C64 brand was reused in 1998 for the Web.it Internet Computer, a low-powered, Internet-oriented, all-in-one x86 PC running MS-DOS and Windows 3.1.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] It uses an AMD Élan SC400 SoC with 16 MB of RAM, a 3.5-inch floppy disk drive, 56k modem and PC Card.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Despite its Commodore 64 nameplate, the C64 Web.it looks different and is only directly compatible with the original via included emulation software.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] PC clones branded C64x sold by Commodore USA, a company licensing the Commodore trademark, began shipping in June 2011.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The C64x's case resembles the original C64 computer, but – like the Web.it – it is based on x86 architecture and is not compatible with the Commodore 64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Several Commodore 64 games were released on the Nintendo Wii's Virtual Console service in Europe and North America.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] They were delisted from the service in August 2013.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] British company Retro Games released two unofficial Linux-based emulation consoles based on the Commodore 64: THEC64 Mini in 2018 and the full size THEC64 in 2019.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The name THEC64 – without a space between "The" and "C64" – is due to Retro Games not licensing the use of any Commodore trademarks including the C64 name; another consequence of this is that the Commodore key from the original keyboard is replaced with a THEC64 key.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] THEC64 Mini is a decorative, half-size Commodore 64 with two USB and one HDMI port, and a mini USB connection to power the system.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The keyboard is non-functional; the system is controlled by an included THEC64 joystick or a separate USB keyboard.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The console uses the VICE emulator which can also load additional software ROMs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The full-size THEC64 is the same size as the original Commodore 64, with a functional keyboard.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Enhancements include VIC-20 emulation, two additional USB ports, and an upgraded joystick.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] In December 2025, the Commodore 64 Ultimate was released by Commodore International.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] It is an FPGA-based remake of the Commodore 64, with added features such as HDMI output and the ability to load software over USB or a Wi-Fi or Ethernet network connection.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] Commodore 64 emulators include the open source VICE, Hoxs64, and CCS64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] An iPhone app was also released with a compilation of C64 ports.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/commodore-64-p02] The *Commodore PET*, introduced in July 2015, was an Android smartphone with Commodore 64 and Amiga emulation built-in.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The **MOS Technology 6502** is an 8-bit microprocessor that was designed by a small team led by Chuck Peddle for MOS Technology and was launched in September 1975.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The design team had formerly worked at Motorola on the Motorola 6800 project; the 6502 is essentially a simplified, less expensive and faster version of that design using depletion-load NMOS technology that made using the microchip in computers much cheaper.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] When it was introduced, the 6502 was the least expensive microprocessor on the market by a considerable margin.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] It initially sold for less than one-sixth the cost of competing designs from larger companies, such as the 6800 or Intel 8080.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Its introduction caused rapid decreases in pricing across the entire processor market.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Along with the Zilog Z80, it sparked a series of projects that resulted in the home computer revolution of the early 1980s.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Home video game consoles and home computers of the 1970s through the early 1990s, such as the Atari 2600, Atari 8-bit computers, Apple II, Nintendo Entertainment System, Commodore 64, Atari Lynx, BBC Micro and others, use the 6502 or variations of the basic design.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Soon after the 6502's introduction, MOS Technology was purchased outright by Commodore International, who continued to sell the microprocessor and licenses to other manufacturers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In the early days of the 6502, it was second-sourced by Rockwell and Synertek, and later licensed to other companies.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In 1981, the Western Design Center started development of a CMOS version, the 65C02.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This continues to be widely used in embedded systems, with estimated production volumes in the hundreds of millions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Motorola started the 6800 microprocessor project in 1971 with Tom Bennett as the main architect.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Bennett hired Chuck Peddle in 1973 to do architectural support work on the 6800 family products already in progress.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Bennett already was at work on what became the 6800.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] "He hired me," Peddle says of Bennett, "to do the architectural support work for the product he'd already started." … Peddle says.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] "Motorola tried to kill it several times.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Without Bennett, the 6800 would not have happened, and a lot of the industry would not have happened, either." Peddle contributed in many areas, including the design of the 6850 ACIA (serial interface).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Peddle would accompany Motorola salespeople on customer visits, and found that customers were put off by the high cost of the microprocessor chips.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] At the same time, these visits invariably resulted in the engineers he presented to producing lists of required instructions that were much smaller than "all these fancy instructions" that had been included in the 6800.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Peddle and other team members started outlining the design of an improved feature, reduced-size microprocessor.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] At that time, Motorola's new semiconductor fabrication facility in Austin, Texas, was having difficulty producing MOS chips, and mid-1974 was the beginning of a year-long recession in the semiconductor industry.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Also, many of the Mesa, Arizona employees were displeased with the upcoming relocation to Austin.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Motorola's Semiconductor Products Division management showed no interest in Peddle's low-cost microprocessor proposal.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Eventually, Peddle was given an official letter telling him to stop working on the system.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Peddle responded to the order by informing Motorola that the letter represented an official declaration of "project abandonment", and as such, the intellectual property he had developed to that point was now his.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The 6502 was designed by many of the same engineers that had designed the Motorola 6800 microprocessor family.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In a November 1975 interview, Motorola's Chairman, Bob Galvin, ultimately agreed that Peddle's concept was a good one and that the division missed an opportunity, "We did not choose the right leaders in the Semiconductor Products division." The division was reorganized and the management replaced.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Peddle began looking outside Motorola for a source of funding for this new project.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Sevin later admitted this was because he was afraid Motorola would sue them.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] While Peddle was visiting Ford Motor Company on one of his sales trips, Bob Johnson, later head of Ford's engine automation division, mentioned that their former colleague John Paivinen had moved to General Instrument and taught himself semiconductor design.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Paivinen then formed MOS Technology in Valley Forge, Pennsylvania in 1969 with two other executives from General Instrument, Mort Jaffe and Don McLaughlin.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Allen-Bradley, a supplier of electronic components and industrial controls, acquired a majority interest in 1970.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The company designed and fabricated custom ICs for customers and had developed a line of calculator chips.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] After the Mostek efforts fell through, Peddle approached Paivinen, who "immediately got it".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] On 19 August 1974, Chuck Peddle, Bill Mensch, Rod Orgill, Harry Bawcom, Ray Hirt, Terry Holdt, and Wil Mathys left Motorola to join MOS.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Of the seventeen chip designers and layout people on the 6800 team, eight left.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The goal of the team was to design and produce a low-cost microprocessor for embedded applications and to target as wide as possible a customer base.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This would be possible only if the microprocessor was low cost, and the team set the price goal for volume purchases at $5.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Mensch later stated the goal was not the processor price itself, but to create a set of chips that could sell at $20 to compete with the recently introduced Intel 4040 that sold for $29 in a similar complete chipset.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Chips are produced by printing multiple copies of the chip design on the surface of a wafer, a thin disk of highly pure silicon.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Smaller chips can be printed in greater numbers on the same wafer, decreasing their relative price.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Additionally, wafers always include some number of tiny physical defects that are scattered across the surface.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Any chip printed in that location will fail and has to be discarded.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Smaller chips mean any single copy is less likely to be printed on a defect.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] For both of these reasons, the cost of the final product is strongly dependent on the size of the chip design.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The original 6800 chips were intended to be 180 by 180 mils (4.6 mm × 4.6 mm), but layout was completed at 212 by 212 mils (5.4 mm × 5.4 mm), or an area of 29.0 mm2.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] For the new design, the cost goal demanded a size goal of 153 by 168 mils (3.9 mm × 4.3 mm), or an area of 16.6 mm2, roughly half that of the 6800.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Several new techniques would be needed to hit this goal.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Two significant advances arrived in the market just as the 6502 was being designed that provided significant cost reductions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The first was the move to depletion-load NMOS.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The 6800 used an early NMOS process, enhancement mode, that required three supply voltages.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] One of the 6800's headlining features was an onboard voltage doubler that allowed a single +5 V supply be used for +5, −5 and +12 V internally, as opposed to other chips of the era like the Intel 8080 that required three separate supply pins.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] While this feature reduced the complexity of the power supply and pin layout, it still required separate power lines to the various gates on the chip, driving up complexity and size.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] By moving to the new depletion-load design, a single +5 V supply was all that was needed, eliminating all of this complexity.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] A further advantage was that depletion-load designs used less power while switching, thus running cooler and allowing higher operating speeds.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Another practical offshoot is that the clock signal for earlier CPUs had to be strong enough to survive all the dissipation as it traveled through the circuits, which almost always required a separate external chip that could supply a powerful signal.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] With the reduced power requirements of depletion-load design, the clock could be moved onto the chip, simplifying the overall computer design.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] These changes greatly reduced complexity and the cost of implementing a complete system.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] A wider change taking place in the industry was the introduction of projection masking.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Previously, chips were patterned onto the surface of the wafer by placing a mask on the surface of the wafer and then shining a bright light on it.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The masks often picked up tiny bits of dirt or photoresist as they were lifted off the chip, causing flaws in those locations on any subsequent masking.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] With complex designs like CPUs, 5 or 6 such masking steps would be used, and the chance that at least one of these steps would introduce a flaw was very high.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In most cases, 90% of such designs were flawed, resulting in a 10% yield.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The price of the working examples had to cover the production cost of the 90% that were thrown away.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In 1973, Perkin-Elmer introduced the Micralign system, which projected an image of the mask on the wafer instead of requiring direct contact.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Masks no longer picked up dirt from the wafers and lasted on the order of 100,000 uses rather than 10.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This eliminated step-to-step failures and the high flaw rates formerly seen on complex designs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Yields on CPUs immediately jumped from 10% to 60 or 70%.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This meant the price of the CPU declined roughly the same amount and the microprocessor suddenly became a commodity device.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] MOS Technology's existing fabrication lines were based on the older PMOS technology, they had not yet begun to work with NMOS when the team arrived.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Paivinen promised to have an NMOS line up and running in time to begin the production of the new CPU.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] He delivered on the promise, the new line was ready by June 1975.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Chuck Peddle, Rod Orgill, and Wil Mathys designed the initial architecture of the new processors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The main change in terms of chip size was the elimination of the tri-state drivers from the address bus outputs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] A three-state bus has states for *1*, *0* and *high impedance*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The last state is used to allow other devices to access the bus, and is typically used for multiprocessing, or more commonly in these roles, for direct memory access (DMA).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] While useful, this feature is expensive in terms of on-chip circuitry.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The 6502 simply removed this feature, in keeping with its design as an inexpensive controller being used for specific tasks and communicating with simple devices.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Peddle suggested that anyone who required this style of access could implement it with a 74158.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The next major difference was to simplify the registers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] To start with, one of the two accumulators was removed.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] General-purpose registers like accumulators have to be accessed by many parts of the instruction decoder, and thus require significant amounts of wiring to move data to and from their storage.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Two accumulators makes many coding tasks easier but costs the chip design itself significant complexity.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Further savings were made by reducing the stack register from 16 to 8 bits, meaning that the stack could only be 256 bytes long, which was enough for its intended role as a microcontroller.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The 16-bit IX index register was split in two, becoming X and Y.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] More importantly, the style of access changed.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In the 6800, IX held a 16-bit address which was offset by an 8-bit number stored with the instruction and added to the address.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In the 6502 (and most other contemporary designs), the 16-bit base address was stored in the instruction, and the 8-bit X or Y was added to it.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Finally, the instruction set was simplified, simplifying the decoder and control logic.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Of the original 72 instructions in the 6800, 56 were implemented.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Among those removed were instructions that operated between the 6800's two accumulators, and several branch instructions inspired by the PDP-11.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The chip's high-level design had to be turned into drawings of transistors and interconnects.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] At MOS Technology, the layout was a very manual process done with colored pencils and vellum paper.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The layout consisted of thousands of polygon shapes on six different drawings; one for each layer of the fabrication process.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Given the size limits, the entire chip design had to be constantly considered.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Mensch and Paivinen worked on the instruction decoder while Mensch, Peddle and Orgill worked on the ALU and registers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] A further advance, developed at a party, was a way to share some of the internal wiring to allow the ALU to be reduced in size.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Despite their best efforts, the final design ended up being larger than the original target.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The original version of the processor had no rotate right (ROR) capability, so the instruction was omitted from the original documentation.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The next iteration of the design shrank the chip and added the rotate right capability, and ROR was included in revised documentation.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] MOS would introduce two microprocessors based on the same underlying design: the 6501 would plug into the same socket as the Motorola 6800, while the 6502 re-arranged the pinout to support an on-chip clock oscillator.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Both would work with other support chips designed for the 6800.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] They would not run 6800 software because they had a different instruction set, different registers, and mostly different addressing modes.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Rod Orgill was responsible for the 6501 design; he had assisted John Buchanan at Motorola on the 6800.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Bill Mensch did the 6502; he was the designer of the 6820 PIA at Motorola.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Harry Bawcom, Mike Janes and Sydney-Anne Holt helped with the layout.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] MOS Technology's microprocessor introduction was different from the traditional months-long product launch.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The first run of a new integrated circuit is normally used for internal testing and shared with select customers as engineering samples.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] These chips often have minor design defects that will be corrected before production begins.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Chuck Peddle's goal was to sell the first run 6501 and 6502 chips to the attendees at the Western Electronics Show and Convention (WESCON) in San Francisco beginning on September 16, 1975.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Peddle was a very effective spokesman and the MOS Technology microprocessors were extensively covered in the trade press.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] One of the earliest was a full-page story on the MCS6501 and MCS6502 microprocessors in the July 24, 1975 issue of *Electronics* magazine.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Advertisements for the 6501 appeared in several publications the first week of August 1975.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The 6501 would be for sale at WESCON for $20 each.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In September 1975, the advertisements included both the 6501 and the 6502 microprocessors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] When MOS Technology arrived at WESCON, they found that exhibitors were not permitted to sell anything on the show floor.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] They rented the MacArthur Suite at the St.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Francis Hotel and directed customers there to purchase the processors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] At the suite, the processors were stored in large jars to imply that the chips were in production and readily available.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The customers did not know the bottom half of each jar contained non-functional chips.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The chips were $20 and $25 while the documentation package was an additional $10.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Users were encouraged to make photocopies of the documents, an inexpensive way for MOS Technology to distribute product information.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The preliminary data sheets listed just 55 instructions and excluded the Rotate Right (ROR) instruction, which was not supported on these early chips.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The reviews in *Byte* and *EDN* noted the lack of the ROR instruction.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The next revision of the layout fixed this problem and the May 1976 datasheet listed 56 instructions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Peddle wanted every interested engineer and hobbyist to have access to the chips and documentation, whereas other semiconductor companies only wanted to deal with "serious" customers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] For example, Signetics was introducing the 2650 microprocessor and its advertisements asked readers to write for information on their company letterhead.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The 6501/6502 introduction in print and at WESCON was a success.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The press coverage got Motorola's attention, precipitating pricing adjustments and lawsuits.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In October 1975, Motorola reduced the price of a single 6800 microprocessor from $175 to $69.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The $300 system design kit was reduced to $150 and it now came with a printed circuit board.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] On November 3, 1975, Motorola sought an injunction in Federal Court to stop MOS Technology from making and selling microprocessor products.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] They also filed a lawsuit claiming patent infringement and misappropriation of trade secrets.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Motorola claimed that seven former employees joined MOS Technology to create that company's microprocessor products.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Motorola was a billion-dollar company with a plausible case and expensive lawyers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] On October 30, 1974, Motorola had filed numerous patent applications on the microprocessor family and was granted twenty-five patents.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The first was in June 1976 and the second was to Bill Mensch on July 6, 1976, for the 6820 PIA chip layout.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] These patents covered the 6800 bus and how the peripheral chips interfaced with the microprocessor.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Motorola began making transistors in 1950 and had a portfolio of semiconductor patents.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Allen-Bradley decided not to fight this case and sold their interest in MOS Technology back to the founders.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Four of the former Motorola engineers were named in the suit: Chuck Peddle, Will Mathys, Bill Mensch and Rod Orgill.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] All were named inventors in the 6800 patent applications.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] During the discovery process, Motorola found that one engineer, Mike Janes, had ignored Peddle's instructions and brought his 6800 design documents to MOS Technology.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In March 1976, the now independent MOS Technology was running out of money and had to settle the case.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] They agreed to drop the 6501 processor, pay Motorola $200,000 and return the documents that Motorola contended were confidential.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Both companies agreed to cross-license microprocessor patents.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] That May, Motorola dropped the price of a single 6800 microprocessor to $35.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] By November, Commodore had acquired MOS Technology.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] With legal troubles behind them, MOS was still left with the problem of getting developers to try their processor, prompting Chuck Peddle to design the MDT650 development system.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Another group inside the company designed the KIM-1, which was sold semi-complete and could be turned into a usable system with the addition of a 3rd party computer terminal and compact cassette drive.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] While it sold well to its intended market, the company found the KIM-1 also sold well to hobbyists and tinkerers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The related Rockwell AIM-65 control, training, and development system also did well.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The software in the AIM 65 was based on that in the MDT.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Another roughly similar product was the Synertek SYM-1.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] One of the first external uses for the design was the Apple I microcomputer, introduced in 1976.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The 6502 was next used in the Commodore PET and Apple II, both released in 1977.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] It was later used in the Atari 8-bit computers, Acorn Atom, BBC Micro, VIC-20 and other designs both for home computers and business, such as Ohio Scientific and Oric computers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The 6510, a direct successor of the 6502 with a digital I/O port and a tri-state address bus, was the CPU utilized in the best-selling Commodore 64 home computer.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Another important use of the 6500 family was in video games.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The first to make use of the processor design was the 1977 Atari VCS, later renamed the Atari 2600.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The VCS used a 6502 variant named the 6507, which had fewer pins, so it could address only 8 KB of memory.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Millions of the Atari consoles would be sold, each with a MOS processor.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Another significant use was by the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES) and Famicom.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The 6502 used in the NES was a second source version by Ricoh, a partial system on a chip, that lacked the binary-coded decimal mode but added 22 memory-mapped registers and on-die hardware for sound generation, joypad reading, and sprite list DMA.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Called 2A03 in NTSC consoles and 2A07 in PAL consoles, this processor was produced exclusively for Nintendo.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] 6502 or variants were used in all of Commodore's floppy disk drives for all of their 8-bit computers, from the PET line through the Commodore 128D, including the Commodore 64.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] 8-inch PET drives had two 6502 processors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Atari used the same 6507 used in the Atari 2600 for its 810 and 1050 disk drives used for all of their 8-bit computer line, from the 400/800 through the XEGS.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In the 1980s, a popular electronics magazine Elektor used the processor in its microprocessor development board Junior Computer.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The CMOS successor to the 6502, the WDC 65C02, also saw use in home computers and video game consoles.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Apple used it in the Apple II line, starting with the Apple IIc and later variants of the Apple IIe, and also offered a kit to upgrade older IIe systems with the new processor.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The Hudson Soft HuC6280 chip used in the TurboGrafx-16 was based on a 65C02 core.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The Atari Lynx used a custom chip named "Mikey" designed by Epyx which included a VLSI VL65NC02 licensed cell.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The G65SC12 by GTE Microcircuits (renamed California Micro Devices) variant was used in the BBC Master.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Some models of the BBC Master also included an additional G65SC102 co-processor.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The 6502 is a little-endian 8-bit processor with a 16-bit address bus.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The original versions were fabricated using an 8 µm process technology with a die size of 3.9 mm × 4.3 mm (153 by 168 mils), for a total area of 16.6 mm2.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The internal logic runs at the same speed as the external clock rate.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] It featured a simple two-stage pipeline; on each cycle, the processor fetches one byte from memory and processes another.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This means that any single instruction can take as few as two cycles to complete, depending on the number of operands that instruction uses.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] For comparison, the Zilog Z80 required two cycles to fetch memory, and the minimum instruction time was four cycles.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Thus, despite the lower clock speeds compared to competing designs, typically in the neighborhood of 1 to 2 MHz, the 6502's performance was competitive with CPUs using significantly faster clocks.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This is partly due to a simple state machine implemented by combinational (clockless) logic to a greater extent than in many other designs; the two-phase clock (supplying two synchronizations per cycle) could thereby control the machine cycle directly.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This design also led to one useful design note of the 6502, and the 6800 before it.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Because the chip only accessed memory during a certain part of the clock cycle, other chips in a system could access memory during those times when the 6502 was off the bus.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This was sometimes known as *hidden access*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This technique was widely used by computer systems; they would use memory capable of access at 2 MHz, and then run the CPU at 1 MHz.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This guaranteed that the CPU and video hardware could interleave their accesses, with a total performance matching that of the memory device.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Because this access was every other cycle, there was no need to signal the CPU to avoid using the bus, making this sort of access easy to implement without any bus logic.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] When faster memories became available in the 1980s, newer machines could use this same technique while running at higher clock rates; the BBC Micro used newer RAM that allowed its CPU to run at 2 MHz while still using the same bus sharing techniques.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Like most simple CPUs of the era, the dynamic NMOS 6502 chip is not sequenced by microcode but decoded directly using a dedicated PLA.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The decoder occupied about 15% of the chip area.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This compares to later microcode-based designs like the Motorola 68000, where the microcode ROM and decoder engine represented about a third of the gates in the system.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Like its precursor, the 6800, the 6502 has very few registers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This compares to a contemporaneous competitor, the Intel 8080, which likewise has one 8-bit accumulator and a 16-bit program counter, but has six more general-purpose 8-bit registers (which can be combined into three 16-bit pointers) and a larger 16-bit stack pointer.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In order to make up somewhat for the lack of registers, the 6502 includes a *zero page* addressing mode that uses one address byte in the instruction instead of the two needed to address the full 64 KB of memory.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This provides fast access to the first 256 bytes of RAM by using shorter instructions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] For instance, an instruction to add a value from memory to the value in the accumulator would normally be three bytes, one for the instruction and two for the 16-bit address.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Using the zero page reduces this to an 8-bit address, reducing the total instruction length to two bytes, and thus improving instruction performance.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Software access to the stack is done via four implied addressing mode instructions, whose functions are to push or pop (pull) the accumulator or the processor status register.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The same stack is also used for subroutine calls via the JSR (jump to subroutine) and RTS (return from subroutine) instructions and for interrupt handling.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] On some 6502-based microcomputers with an operating system, the operating system uses most of the zero page, leaving only a handful of locations for the user.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Addressing modes also include *implied* (1-byte instructions); *absolute* (3 bytes); *indexed absolute* (3 bytes); *indexed zero-page* (2 bytes); *relative* (2 bytes); *accumulator* (1); *indirect,x* and *indirect,y* (2); and *immediate* (2).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Accumulator mode operates on the accumulator register and does not need any operand data.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Immediate mode uses an 8-bit literal operand.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The indirect modes are useful for array processing and pointer-based data structures.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] With the 5 or 6 cycle *indirect,y* mode, the 8-bit Y register is added to a 16-bit base address read from zero page, which is located by a single byte following the opcode.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The Y register is therefore an *index* register in the sense that it is used to hold an actual *index*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Incrementing the index register to walk the array byte-wise takes only two additional cycles.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] With the less frequently used *indirect,x* mode, the effective address for the operation is found at the zero page address formed by adding the second byte of the instruction to the contents of the X register.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Using the indexed modes, the zero page effectively acts as a set of up to 128 additional (low-performance) address registers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The 6502 is capable of performing addition and subtraction in binary or binary-coded decimal.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Placing the CPU into BCD mode with the `SED` (set D flag) instruction results in decimal arithmetic, in which `$99 + $01` would result in *$00* and the carry (C) flag being set.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In binary mode, entered with `CLD` (clear D flag), the same operation would result in *$9A* and the carry flag being cleared.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Other than Atari BASIC, BCD mode was seldom used in home-computer applications.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] 6502 instruction operation codes (*opcodes*) are 8 bits long and have the general form AAABBBCC, where AAA and CC define the opcode, and BBB defines the addressing mode.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] For example, the `ORA` instruction performs a bitwise OR on the bits in the accumulator with another value.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The instruction opcode is of the form 000BBB01, where BBB may be 010 for an immediate mode value (constant), 001 for zero-page fixed address, 011 for an absolute address, and so on.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This pattern is not universal, as there are exceptions, but it allows opcode values to be easily converted to assembly mnemonics for the majority of instructions, handling the edge cases with special-purpose code.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Of the 256 possible opcodes available using an 8-bit pattern, the original 6502 uses 151 of them, organized into 56 instructions with (possibly) multiple addressing modes.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Depending on the instruction and addressing mode, the opcode may require zero, one or two additional bytes for operands.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Hence 6502 machine instructions vary in length from one to three bytes.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The operand is stored in the 6502's customary little-endian format.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Each CPU machine instruction takes up a certain number of clock cycles, usually equal to the number of memory accesses.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] For example, the absolute indexing mode of the ORA instruction takes 4 clock cycles; 3 cycles to read the instruction and 1 cycle to read the value of the absolute address.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] If no memory is accessed, the number of clock cycles is two.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The minimum clock cycles for any instruction is two.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] When using indexed addressing, if the result crosses a page boundary an extra clock cycle is added.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Also, when a zero page address is used in indexing mode (e.g. zp,X) an extra clock cycle is added.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The 65C816, the 16-bit CMOS descendant of the 6502, also supports 24-bit addressing, which results in instructions being assembled with three-byte operands, also arranged in little-endian format.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The remaining 105 opcodes are undefined.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] In the original design, instructions where the low-order 4 bits (*nibble*) were 3, 7, B or F were not used, providing room for future expansion.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Likewise, the $x2 column had only a single entry, `LDX #*constant*`.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The remaining 25 empty slots were distributed.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Some of the empty slots were used in the 65C02 to provide both new instructions and variations on existing ones with new addressing modes.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The $xF instructions were initially left free to allow 3rd-party vendors to add their own instructions, but later versions of the 65C02 standardized a set of bit manipulation instructions developed by Rockwell Semiconductor.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] A 6502 assembly language statement consists of a three-character instruction mnemonic, followed by any operands.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Instructions that do not take a separate operand but target a single register based on the addressing mode combine the target register in the instruction mnemonic, so the assembler uses `INX` as opposed to `INC X` to increment the X register.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] are undefined in the 6502 instruction set.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The following 6502 assembly language source code is for a subroutine named `TOLOWER`, which copies a null-terminated character string from one location to another, converting upper-case letter characters to lower-case letters.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The string being copied is the "source", and the string into which the converted source is stored is the "destination".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The processor's non-maskable interrupt (NMI) input is edge sensitive, which means that the interrupt is triggered by the falling edge of the signal rather than its level.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Consequently a wired-OR interrupt circuit cannot be readily supported.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] However, this also prevents nested NMI interrupts from occurring until the interrupt source hardware makes the NMI input inactive again, often under control of the NMI interrupt handler.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The simultaneous assertion of the NMI and IRQ (maskable) hardware interrupt lines causes IRQ to be ignored.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] However, if the IRQ line remains asserted after the servicing of the NMI, the processor will almost immediately respond to IRQ, as IRQ is level sensitive.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] Thus a sort of built-in interrupt priority was established in the 6502 design.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The B flag is set by the 6502's periodically sampling its NMI edge detector's output and its IRQ input.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The IRQ signal being driven low is only recognized though if IRQs are not masked by the I flag.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] If in this way a NMI request or (maskable) IRQ is detected the B flag is set to zero and causes the processor to execute the BRK instruction next instead of executing the next instruction based on the program counter.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The BRK instruction then pushes the processor status onto the stack, with the B flag bit set to zero.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] At the end of its execution the BRK instruction resets the B flag's value to one.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This is the only way the B flag can be modified.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] If an instruction other than the BRK instruction pushes the B flag onto the stack as part of the processor status the B flag always has the value one.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] A high-to-low transition on the SO input pin will set the processor's overflow status bit.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] This can be used for fast response to external hardware.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] For example, a high-speed polling device driver can poll the hardware once in only three cycles using a Branch-on-oVerflow-Clear (`BVC`) instruction that branches to itself until overflow is set by an SO falling transition.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The Commodore 1541 and other Commodore floppy disk drives use this technique to detect when the serializer is ready to transfer another byte of disk data.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p01] The system hardware and software design must ensure that an SO will not occur during arithmetic processing and disrupt calculations.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] The 6502 was the most prolific variant of the 65xx series family from MOS Technology.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] The 6501 and 6502 have 40-pin DIP packages; the 6503, 6504, 6505, and 6507 are 28-pin DIP versions, for reduced chip and circuit board cost.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] In all of the 28-pin versions, the pin count is reduced by leaving off some of the high-order address pins and various combinations of function pins, making those functions unavailable.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] The omission of four address pins reduces the external addressability to 4 KB (from the 64 KB of the 6502), though the internal PC register and all effective address calculations remain 16-bit.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] The 6507 omits both interrupt pins in order to include address line A12, providing 8 KB of external addressability but no interrupt capability.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] One popular 6502-based computer, the Commodore 64, used a modified 6502 CPU, the 6510.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] Unlike the 6503–6505 and 6507, the 6510 is a 40-pin chip that adds internal hardware: a 6-bit parallel I/O port mapped to addresses 0000 and 0001.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] The 6508 is another chip that, like the 6510, adds internal hardware: 256 bytes of SRAM and an 8-bit I/O port similar to those featured by the 6510.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] Though these chips do not have reduced pin counts compared to the 6502, they need new pins for the added parallel I/O port.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] In this case, no address lines are among the removed pins.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] The Western Design Center designed and, as of 2025, still produces the WDC 65C816S processor, a 16-bit, static-core successor to the 65C02.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] The W65C816S is a newer variant of the 65C816, which is the core of the Apple IIGS computer and is the basis of the Ricoh 5A22 processor that powers the Super Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] The W65C816S incorporates minor improvements over the 65C816 that make the newer chip not an exact hardware-compatible replacement for the earlier one.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] Among these improvements was conversion to a static core, which makes it possible to stop the clock in either phase without the registers losing data.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] Available through electronics distributors, as of March 2020, the W65C816S is officially rated for 14 MHz operation.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] The Western Design Center also designed and produced the 65C802, which was a 65C816 core with a 64-kilobyte address space in a 65(C)02 pin-compatible package.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] The 65C802 could be retrofitted to a 6502 board and would function as a 65C02 on power-up, operating in "emulation mode." As with the 65C816, a two-instruction sequence would switch the 65C802 to "native mode" operation, exposing its 16-bit accumulator and index registers, and other 65C816 features.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/mos-technology-6502-p02] The 65C802 was not widely used and production ended.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The **Nintendo Entertainment System** (**NES**) is a home video game console developed and marketed by Nintendo.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] It was released as the**Family Computer** (**Famicom**) in Japan on July 15, 1983, and as the NES in test markets in the United States on October 18, 1985, followed by a nationwide launch on September 27, 1986.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The NES was distributed in Europe, Australia, and parts of Asia throughout the 1980s.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] It was Nintendo's first programmable home console, succeeding the Color TV-Game line of dedicated consoles, and primarily competed with Sega's Master System in the third generation of video game consoles.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The engineer Masayuki Uemura designed the 8-bit Famicom after Nintendo's president Hiroshi Yamauchi called for a simple, cheap console that could run arcade games from cartridges.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Its hardware was based on that of Nintendo's arcade game *Donkey Kong* (1981) and its controller design was reused from Nintendo's portable Game & Watch hardware.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] For Western markets, Lance Barr and Don James redesigned it as the NES to resemble a video cassette recorder.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] To aid its acceptance in stores, Nintendo released add-ons such as the Zapper, a light gun for shooting games, and R.O.B., a toy robot.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In Japan, Nintendo released the Famicom Disk System add-on to distribute games on floppy disks, although it gradually reduced support for the peripheral due to hardware constraints.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo released the NES in the aftermath of the video game crash of 1983.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In Japan and North America, it quickly dominated and gave Nintendo a near-monopoly on the home console market.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Unlike the previous market leader, Atari, Nintendo sought the support of third-party developers, such as Capcom, Hudson Soft, Konami, Namco, Enix, and Square.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Its restrictive licensing terms, which included platform exclusivity and a five-game-per-year limit, led to accusations of antitrust violations in the US, culminating in a 1991 settlement with the Federal Trade Commission.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo sold 61.91 million consoles; though dominant in Japan and North America, the NES performed less well in Europe, where it faced competition from the Master System and home computers such as the Commodore 64 and ZX Spectrum.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo released a successor, the Super Nintendo Entertainment System, in 1990, but continued to support the NES into the 16-bit era.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] It ceased NES production in 1995 and Famicom production in 2003.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The NES is regarded as one of the most influential consoles, as it helped revitalize the American gaming industry following the 1983 crash and pioneered the now-standard business model of licensing third-party developers to produce and distribute games.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Several NES games, including *Super Mario Bros.* (1985), *The Legend of Zelda* (1986), *Dragon Quest* (1986), and *Final Fantasy* (1987), became major franchises.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The video game industry experienced rapid growth and popularity from the late 1970s to the early 1980s, marked by the golden age of arcade games and the second generation of consoles.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Games like *Space Invaders* (1978) became a phenomenon across arcades worldwide, while home consoles such as the Atari 2600 and home computers such as the Commodore 64 and the Intellivision gained a foothold in the American market.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Many companies emerged to capitalize on the growing industry, including the card and toy company Nintendo.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo president Hiroshi Yamauchi realized that breakthroughs in the electronics industry meant that entertainment products could be produced at lower prices.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Companies such as Atari and Magnavox were already selling gaming devices for use with television sets to moderate success.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Yamauchi negotiated a license with Magnavox for the patents on the technology used in the Magnavox Odyssey.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Since Nintendo's operation was not yet sophisticated enough to design its own hardware, Yamauchi forged an alliance with Mitsubishi Electric and hired several Sharp Electronics employees to assist in developing the Color TV-Game 6 and the Color TV-Game 15 in Japan.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] This was followed by the handheld Game & Watch series.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The successes of these consoles gave Yamauchi the confidence to expand Nintendo's influence in the fledgling video game industry.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In 1978, Yamauchi split Nintendo into separate research and development divisions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] He appointed Masayuki Uemura as head of Nintendo Research & Development 2.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Yamauchi, through extensive discussions with Uemura and other engineers, recognized the potential of the developing console beyond gaming.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] He envisioned a home computer system disguised as a toy, which could significantly expand Nintendo's reach if it became popular with children.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] This popularity would drive demand for games, with Nintendo as the sole provider.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Indeed, by 1980 several systems had already been released in Japan by both American and Japanese companies.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Yamauchi tasked Uemura with developing a system that would be superior to its competitors and difficult to replicate for at least a year.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Uemura's main challenge was economic rather than technological; Yamauchi wanted the system to be affordable enough for widespread household adoption, aiming for a price of ¥9,800 (less than $75) compared to existing machines priced at ¥30,000 to ¥50,000 ($200 to $350).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The new system had to outperform other systems, both Japanese and American, while being significantly more affordable.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] As development progressed on the new video game system, engineers sought Yamauchi's guidance on its features.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] They questioned whether to include a disk drive, keyboard, data port, as well as the potential for a modem, expanded memory, and other computer-like capabilities.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Yamauchi ultimately instructed Uemura to prioritize simplicity and affordability, omitting these peripherals entirely.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Game cartridges, which Uemura saw as "less intimidating" to consumers, were chosen as the format.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The team designed the system with 2,000 bytes of random-access memory (RAM).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The console's hardware was largely based on arcade video games, particularly the hardware for Namco's *Galaxian* (1979) and Nintendo's own *Donkey Kong* (1981), with the goal of matching their powerful sprite and scrolling capabilities in a home system.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] A test model was constructed in October 1982 to verify the functionality of the hardware, and work began on programming tools.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Because 65xx CPUs had not been manufactured or sold in Japan by that time, no cross-development software was available, and had to be developed from scratch.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Early Famicom games were written on a PC-8001 computer.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] LEDs on a grid were used with a digitizer to design graphics, as no such software design tools existed at the time.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The codename for the project was GameCom, but Masayuki Uemura's wife proposed the name **Famicom**, arguing that "In Japan, 'pasokon' is used to mean a personal computer, but it is neither a home nor personal computer.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Perhaps we could say it is a family computer." Meanwhile, Yamauchi decided that the console should use a red and white color scheme after seeing a hoarding for DX Antenna (a Japanese antenna manufacturer) that used those colors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The Famicom was influenced by the ColecoVision, Coleco's competition against the Atari 2600 in the United States; the ColecoVision's top-seller was a port of Nintendo's *Donkey Kong*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The project's chief manager Takao Sawano brought a ColecoVision home to his family, who was impressed by its smooth graphics, which contrasted with the flicker and slowdown commonly seen on Atari 2600 games.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Uemura said the ColecoVision set the bar for the Famicom.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The team, wanting to surpass the ColecoVision and match the more powerful *Donkey Kong* arcade hardware, took a *Donkey Kong* arcade cabinet to chip manufacturer Ricoh for analysis, which led to Ricoh producing the Picture Processing Unit (PPU) chip for the Famicom.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Kaneoka therefore designed the Famicom's sound chip to be able to render a wider variety of waveforms than was common in either consoles or home computers at the time.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] During development, Yamauchi directed engineers to reduce costs by removing non-essential components.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] However, he insisted on including a low-cost circuit and connector that allowed the CPU to send or receive unmodified signals, enabling future hardware expansions such as modems or keyboards.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] This built-in capability led some within Nintendo to refer to the console as "Yamauchi's Trojan Horse": it entered homes as a simple gaming device with two controllers, and yet contained features far beyond its apparent function.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Design decisions were also carefully considered.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Yamauchi took a hands-on role in determining the controller layout, casing shape, and overall aesthetic.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The final design featured a directional pad and two buttons on the right controller, a microphone on the left controller, rounded edges, and a red and white color scheme deliberately made to appear more like a toy than a computer.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Original plans called for the Famicom's cartridges to be the size of a cassette tape, but they ultimately ended up being twice as large.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Careful design attention was paid to the cartridge connectors, as loose and faulty connections often plagued arcade machines.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Because it necessitated 60 connection lines for the memory and expansion, Nintendo decided to produce its own connectors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Each cartridge typically contained two primary chips: one for the game’s program code (up to 32 kilobytes), and another for graphical data used to render on-screen characters (up to 8 kilobytes).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo's R&D3 team designed the "UNROM" cartridge, which enabled larger memory capacities and the use of bank switching.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] This technique involved storing additional data in RAM and dynamically accessing it as needed, thereby significantly expanding gameplay possibilities.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] At Gunpei Yokoi's suggestion, a cartridge eject lever was also added, not for functionality, but to amuse children.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The Famicom design team initially considered arcade-style joysticks, and even dismantled existing models from American consoles, but ultimately rejected them due to concerns about durability and the risk of children stepping on them.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Instead, they adopted the D-pad and two action button layout developed by R&D1 for their handheld Game & Watch series.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] As an early prototype, Katsuya Nakagawa attached a Game & Watch D-pad to the Famicom and found it comfortable and easy to use.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] To reduce costs, the controllers were hardwired to the console and stored in molded pockets on the case.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] A 15-pin expansion port was added to the front of the console so that an optional arcade-style joystick could be used.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The second controller also included a microphone, which Uemura envisioned being used to make players' voices come through the TV speaker.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] On July 15, 1983, the console was released in Japan as the **Home Cassette Type Video Game: Family Computer**, priced at ¥14,800 (¥20,718 in 2025) with three launch games, all of which were ports of popular Nintendo arcade games: *Donkey Kong* (1981), *Donkey Kong Jr.* (1982), and *Popeye* (1982).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Although it was priced higher than originally intended, the Famicom remained less than half the cost of rival consoles.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Backed by a robust marketing campaign, 500,000 units were sold within the first two months.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] However, a major fault emerged ahead of the critical Japanese New Year season, as reports began surfacing of consoles crashing during gameplay.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Uemura and engineer Gunpei Yokoi traced the issue to a defective integrated circuit that could lock under specific data conditions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Upon reporting the issue to Yamauchi, staff proposed selectively replacing affected units.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] However, they were warned that a partial response could damage consumer trust and jeopardize Nintendo's first-mover advantage before competitors could respond.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] After a product recall and the release of a revised model with a new motherboard, the system's popularity soared.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] By the end of 1984, the Famicom had become the best-selling game console in Japan in what came to be called the "Famicom Boom".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Following the sale of the first million units, demand showed no signs of slowing.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Japanese retailers inundated Nintendo with urgent requests for stock.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Anticipation for new game releases reached record levels, which resulted in long queues and games selling out instantly.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] This phenomenon, soon dubbed "Nintendomania", overwhelmed the supply chain and further increased demand.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The Famicom's success quickly cleared the field of competition in Japan.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Fourteen rival console manufacturers exited the market, and Sega's SG-1000, launched in Japan on the same day as the Famicom, failed to gain traction.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] At launch, Nintendo released only first-party games for the Famicom.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] However, in 1984, after being approached by Namco and Hudson Soft, the company agreed to allow third-party titles.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Developers paid a 30% fee to cover console licensing and production costs, a revenue model that would later influence the video game industry for decades.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo initially planned for the console to enter the North American market through a distribution agreement with Atari.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The agreement was expected to be finalized at the Summer Consumer Electronics Show (CES) in June 1983.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] However, during the show, Atari discovered that Coleco was demonstrating an unlicensed port of Nintendo's *Donkey Kong* on its Adam computer system.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Atari, believing this violated its exclusive license for the game, delayed the deal.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Shortly afterward, Atari CEO Ray Kassar was fired, the deal fell apart, and Nintendo decided to market its system on its own.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo believed that the Famicom name might not resonate with American consumers, and initially rebranded the console as the **Advanced Video System** (AVS).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The AVS resembled a home computer rather than a "toy", featuring a built-in keyboard, a cassette-based data drive, and infrared wireless controllers.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] By positioning the console as a more "sophisticated" consumer electronics product, Nintendo aimed to distance itself from the recent failures of companies such as Atari, Coleco, and Mattel.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The AVS was publicly demonstrated at the Winter CES in January 1985, but the reaction was lukewarm.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] While the hardware and games were praised, there was deep skepticism that the console could succeed in the United States, as the industry there was still recovering from the video game crash of 1983.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] *Electronic Games* magazine reported in March 1985 that the video game market in America "[had] virtually disappeared", and believed "[it] could be a miscalculation on Nintendo's part".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] With American retailers still wary of stocking game consoles after the 1983 crash, Yamauchi saw an opportunity to introduce the Famicom's hardware to North America through arcades.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] System, an arcade conversion system that featured ports of select Famicom games, with a focus on two-player competitive play.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] System became a major success, selling nearly 100,000 cabinets and becoming the highest-grossing arcade machine of 1985 in the United States.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] This success gave Nintendo the confidence to pursue a home console launch in North America, and provided a platform to test new titles to help shape the launch line-up.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo of America designers Lance Barr and Don James were disappointed with the prototype console they received from Japan, which they nicknamed "the lunchbox".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] For the console's western redesign, they added a two-tone gray color scheme with a black stripe and red lettering, as well as a front-loading, zero insertion force slot modeled after a videocassette recorder which concealed the game cartridge once inserted.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The redesigned console, now called the **Nintendo Entertainment System** (NES), was unveiled by Nintendo at the June 1985 Summer CES, and dropped the home computer features of the earlier AVS prototype while retaining its gray color scheme and boxy form factor.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] It also replaced the Famicom's hardwired controllers and the AVS's wireless ones with detachable wired controllers using proprietary 7-pin connectors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] To avoid the language used by earlier game consoles, marketing manager Gail Tilden coined alternative terms for the NES's hardware, calling the cartridges "Game Paks" and the console itself the "Control Deck", which would later aid its acceptance in toy stores.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] To further distance the NES from previous consoles, Nintendo heavily promoted optional accessories, such as the Zapper light gun and the Robotic Operating Buddy (R.O.B.), to position the system as cutting-edge and sophisticated.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] While initial consumer interest in the console was limited, its peripherals drew significant attention.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The NES launched in a limited test market in New York City on October 18, 1985, followed by Los Angeles in February 1986, and finally a full North American release on September 27, 1986.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The launch line-up included 17 games: *10-Yard Fight*, *Baseball*, *Clu Clu Land*, *Duck Hunt*, *Excitebike*, *Golf*, *Gyromite*, *Hogan's Alley*, *Ice Climber*, *Kung Fu*, *Pinball*, *Soccer*, *Stack-Up*, *Super Mario Bros.*, *Tennis*, *Wild Gunman*, and *Wrecking Crew*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo contracted with toy company Worlds of Wonder (WoW) to get the NES distributed in stores.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] WoW's aggressive sales tactics, which included requiring retailers to carry the NES in order to sell WoW's other popular toys, helped secure shelf space for the console.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] With the launch of the NES, Nintendo redefined the home video game market in North America.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The 1983 crash had been fueled by misleading marketing, lack of quality control, and hardware fragmentation.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In contrast, Nintendo introduced strict standards for software approval, packaging, and quality.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] It used consistent branding with genre icons, box art that reflected in-game graphics, and the "Official Nintendo Seal of Quality".
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] To enforce its standards, the company used the 10NES lock-out chip to deter production of unlicensed games.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In Europe and Oceania, the NES was released in two separate marketing regions.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The first consisted of mainland Europe (excluding Italy), where distribution was handled by several different companies, with Nintendo responsible for manufacturing.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The NES saw an early launch in Europe in 1986, although most European countries received the console in 1987.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In Scandinavia, it was released on September 1, 1986, and was distributed by Bergsala.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In the Netherlands, it was released in the last quarter of 1987, and was distributed by Bandai BV.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In France, it was released in October 1987, and in Spain most likely in 1988 through distributor Spaco.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In 1987, Mattel handled distribution for the second region, consisting of the United Kingdom, Ireland, Italy, Australia and New Zealand.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In other European countries, distribution was handled by smaller companies like Bienengräber in Germany, ASD in France, Concentra in Portugal, Itochu in Greece and Cyprus, and Stadlbauer in Austria, Switzerland, and the former Eastern Bloc.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In Poland, the NES had its release on October 6, 1994, along with the SNES and the Game Boy.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In November 1994, Nintendo signed an agreement with Steepler to permit the continued sale of the Dendy, an unauthorized hardware clone of the Famicom, in Russia in exchange for also distributing the SNES.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo anticipated that the NES would have a 25 percent market share in Europe, and saw particular potential in the United Kingdom.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The console struggled to gain a foothold in the region, however, in part due to the widespread popularity of the ZX Spectrum, which had already established a strong home computing and gaming culture.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The affordability, local software support, and versatility of the Spectrum also made it a dominant choice among British consumers, which severely limited the NES's market penetration.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The console would see an increase in share in 1990 with the release of the *Teenage Mutant Hero Turtles* bundle, which was released against Nintendo of America's wishes but ultimately allowed the console's European sales to overtake those of the Master System.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In Brazil, the console was officially released in late 1993 by Playtronic.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] However, the Brazilian market had been dominated by unlicensed NES clones that were either locally made or smuggled from Taiwan.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] One of the most successful Brazilian NES clones was the Phantom System by Gradiente, which licensed Nintendo products in the country for the following decade.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The sales of officially licensed products in the region were low due to the abundance of clones, the console's official launch coming after the SNES, and the high prices of Nintendo's licensed products.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Outside of Japan, regions of Bangladesh, Indonesia, Malaysia, Nepal, Pakistan, Singapore, Sri Lanka and Thailand received an "Asian version" of the front-loader NES, although imported Famicom systems were still prevalent.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Due to import restrictions, NES consoles in India and South Korea were rebranded and distributed by local licenses.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The Korean version is known as the Hyundai Comboy, and the Indian version is known as the Samurai Electronic TV Game System.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] India was the third region outside of North America and Japan to officially receive the NES.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] It was produced locally by Samurai Electronics in North India, and was released to strong initial sales in the region, selling 3,000 units per month.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] However, in the early 1990s, when retailers began promoting bootleg consoles, the console saw a significant drop in sales, selling 300 units per month.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The NES was released in several retail bundles throughout its commercial life.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] For its 1985 American test launch, the initial offering was the Deluxe Set, which retailed for US$179.99 (equivalent to $540 in 2025) and included the Control Deck, two controllers, the NES Zapper light gun, the R.O.B. robotic accessory, and two Game Paks: *Gyromite* and *Duck Hunt*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Ahead of the console's nationwide launch in 1986, Nintendo introduced a basic Control Deck set with two controllers, bundled with *Super Mario Bros.* for US$99.99 (equivalent to $280 in 2025).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In 1988, the Deluxe Set was replaced by the Action Set, which retailed for US$99.99 (equivalent to $270 in 2025) and bundled the Control Deck with two controllers, the NES Zapper, and a dual Game Pak containing *Super Mario Bros.* and *Duck Hunt*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] 1988 also saw the introduction of the Power Set, which added the Power Pad floor mat game controller and replaced the dual cartridge with a triple Game Pak featuring *Super Mario Bros.*, *Duck Hunt*, and *World Class Track Meet*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In 1990, Nintendo released the Sports Set, which included the Control Deck, four controllers, an NES Satellite infrared wireless multitap adapter, and a dual Game Pak containing *Super Spike V'Ball* and *Nintendo World Cup*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In 1992, the Challenge Set debuted at US$89.99 (equivalent to $210 in 2025), featuring the Control Deck and two controllers, bundled with *Super Mario Bros.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Finally, in October 1993, Nintendo released a redesigned version of the console, known as the New-Style NES or NES-101, in North America, Australia, and Japan.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] This version included a single redesigned "dogbone" shape controller, and retailed for US$49.99 (equivalent to $110 in 2025) in North America before its discontinuation in 1995.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In Australia, the console was bundled with a triple Game Pak featuring *Super Mario Bros.*, *Tetris*, and *Nintendo World Cup*, and sold for A$79.99, or A$69.99 without the bundled Game Pak.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] On August 14, 1995, Nintendo discontinued the Nintendo Entertainment System in both North America and Europe.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In North America, replacements for the original front-loading NES were available for $25 in exchange for a broken system until at least December 1996, under Nintendo's Power Swap program.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In September 2003, Nintendo discontinued the Famicom in Japan, alongside the Super Famicom and disk rewriting services for the Famicom Disk System.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo offered repair services for the Famicom in Japan until 2007, when it was discontinued due to a shortage of available parts.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Although all versions of the Famicom and NES include essentially similar hardware, they vary in physical characteristics.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In contrast, the design of the original NES features a more subdued gray, black, and red color scheme, with a front-loading cartridge slot covered by a small, hinged door that can be opened to insert or remove a cartridge and closed at other times, and an expansion port on the bottom of the unit.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The NES also includes the 10NES lock-out chip, and incorporates a matching chip validation check in its cartridge connector.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In late 1993, Nintendo introduced a redesigned version of the Famicom and NES (known officially as the New Famicom in Japan and the New-Style NES in the US) to complement the Super Famicom and SNES, to prolong interest in the console, and to reduce costs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The redesigned NES features a top-loading cartridge slot and omits the 10NES lock-out chip to avoid reliability issues with the original console; the redesign also omits AV output.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Conversely, the redesigned Famicom features AV output, and introduces detachable game controllers, which ultimately omitted microphone functionality as a result.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The redesigned Famicom and NES models are cosmetically similar, aside from the presence of a cartridge "bump" on the NES model, which the Famicom model lacks to accommodate its shorter cartridges and the RAM Adapter for the Famicom Disk System.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Sharp Corporation produced three licensed variants of the Famicom in Japan, all of which prominently display the shortened moniker rather than the official name, Family Computer.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] One variant was a television set with an integrated Famicom; originally released in 1983 as the My Computer TV in 14-inch (36 cm) and 19-inch (48 cm) models, it was later released in the United States in 1989 as a 19-inch model named the Video Game Television.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Another variant is the Twin Famicom console, which was released in 1986 and combines a Famicom with a Famicom Disk System.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Sharp then produced the Famicom Titler in 1989; intended for video capture and production, it features internal RGB video generation and video output via S-Video, as well as inputs for adding subtitles and voice-overs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] A thriving market of unlicensed NES hardware clones emerged during the climax of the console's popularity.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Initially, such clones were popular in markets with weak copyright laws and countries in which Nintendo issued its systems after "famiclones" became well-known, making legal products difficult to market or create brand awareness for.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In particular, the Dendy (Russian: Де́нди), an unlicensed hardware clone produced in Taiwan and sold in the former Soviet Union by Steepler, emerged as the most popular console of its time, eventually selling six million units.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In Poland, the Pegasus clone, distributed by Bobmark International, sold more than a million units.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In China, a reported 30 million units were sold until late 1995.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] A range of Famicom clones was marketed in Latin America during the late 1980s and 1990s under the name "Family Game", resembling the original hardware design.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The Ending-Man Terminator clone enjoyed popularity in the Eastern Bloc, as well as in parts of Africa, Asia, and Latin America.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The unlicensed clone market flourished following Nintendo's discontinuation of the NES.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Some of these surpass the functionality of the original hardware, such as PocketFami, a portable system with a color LCD screen.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Others have been produced for certain specialized markets, such as a personal computer with a keyboard and basic word processing software.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] These unauthorised clones have been helped by the invention of the so-called NES-on-a-chip.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo's design styling for the NES's North American release was made deliberately different from that of other game consoles.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The company wished to distinguish their product from those of competitors and avoid the generally poor reputation that game consoles had acquired following the video game crash of 1983.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] One result of this philosophy was to disguise the cartridge slot design as a front-loading zero-insertion force (ZIF) cartridge socket, designed to resemble the front-loading mechanism of a videocassette recorder.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] However, when a user inserts the cartridge, the force of pressing it into place bends the contact pins slightly and presses the cartridge's ROM board back into the cartridge.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Frequent insertion and removal of cartridges can wear out the pins, and the ZIF design has proven to be more prone to interference by dirt and dust than an industry-standard card edge connector.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The design problems were exacerbated by Nintendo's choice of materials.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The console slot nickel connector springs wear out due to their design, and the game cartridge's brass plated nickel connectors are also prone to tarnishing and oxidation.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo sought to fix these problems by redesigning the next generation Super Nintendo Entertainment System (SNES) as a top loader similar to the Famicom.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Many users reportedly tried to alleviate issues caused by corrosion by blowing into the cartridges and then reinserting them, which conversely sped up the tarnishing due to moisture.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The Famicom as released in Japan contains no lock-out hardware, which led to unlicensed cartridges (both legitimate and bootleg) becoming extremely common in Japan and East Asia.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] To combat bootlegs, Nintendo attempted to promote its "Seal of Quality" in these regions to identify licensed games, but bootleg Famicom games continued to be produced even after Nintendo moved production onto the Super Famicom, effectively extending the lifetime of the original Famicom.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The original NES, released for western countries in 1985, contains the 10NES lock-out chip, which prevents the console from running cartridges unapproved by Nintendo.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The inclusion of the 10NES chip was a result of the 1983 North American video game crash, which was partially caused by a market flooded with uncontrolled publishing of poor-quality home console games.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo sought to use the lock-out chip to restrict games to only those they licensed for the system.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] This means of protection worked in combination with Nintendo's "Seal of Quality", which a developer had to acquire before they would be able to have access to the required 10NES information prior to publication of a game.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Original NES consoles sold in different regions have different lock-out chips, thereby enforcing regional lock-out regardless of TV signal compatibility.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Such regions include North America; most of continental Europe (PAL-B); Asia; and the British Isles, Italy, and Australasia (PAL-A).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Problems with the 10NES lock-out chip frequently result in one of the console's most common issues: the blinking, red power light, in which the system appears to turn itself on and off repeatedly because the 10NES would reset the console once per second.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The lock-out chip requires constant communication with the chip in the game to work.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The console's main central processing unit (CPU) was produced by Ricoh, which manufactured different versions for NTSC and PAL regions; NTSC consoles have a 2A03 clocked at 1.79 MHzTooltip megahertz, and PAL consoles have a 2A07 clocked at 1.66 MHz.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Both CPUs are unlicensed variants of the MOS Technology 6502, an 8-bit microprocessor prevalent in contemporary home computers and consoles.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo ostensibly disabled the 6502's binary-coded decimal mode on them to avoid patent infringement against or licensing fees towards MOS Technology, which was owned by then-rival Commodore International.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The CPU has access to 2 KBTooltip kilobyte of onboard work RAMTooltip random-access memory.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The console's graphics are handled by a Ricoh 2C02, a processor known as the Picture Processing Unit (PPU) that is clocked at 5.37 MHz.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Each sprite tile can display up to 3 palette colors at a time, with the first entry of each palette representing transparency.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The console's standard display resolution is 256 × 240 pixels, though video output options vary between models.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The original Famicom features only radio frequency (RF) modulator output, and the NES additionally supports composite video via RCA connectors.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The console produces sound via an audio processing unit (APU) integrated into the processor.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] It supports a total of five sound channels: two pulse wave channels, one triangle wave channel, one white noise channel, and one DPCMTooltip differential pulse-code modulation channel for sample playback.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Audio playback speed is dependent on the CPU clock rate, which is set by a crystal oscillator.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The game controller for both the NES and the Famicom has an oblong brick-like design with a simple four button layout: two round buttons labelled "A" and "B", a "START" button, and a "SELECT" button.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Additionally, the controllers use the cross-shaped D-pad, designed by Nintendo employee Gunpei Yokoi for Game & Watch systems, to replace the bulkier joysticks of controllers used by earlier gaming consoles.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The original model Famicom features two game controllers, both of which are hardwired to the back of the console.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The second controller lacks the Start and Select buttons, and instead features a small microphone; however, few games use this feature.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The earliest produced Famicom units have square A and B buttons; issues with them getting stuck when pressed down led Nintendo to change their shape to a circular design in subsequent units following the console's recall.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] In contrast to the Famicom's hardwired controllers, the NES has two proprietary seven-pin ports on the front of the console to support detachable controllers and third-party peripherals.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The controllers bundled with the NES are identical and include the Start and Select buttons, lacking the microphone on the original Famicom's second controller.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The cables for NES controllers are also generally three times longer than their Famicom counterparts.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Several special controllers are intended for use with specific games but not commonly used.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Such peripherals include the NES Zapper (a light gun), R.O.B.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] (a toy robot), and the Power Pad (a dance pad).
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The original Famicom has a deepened DA-15 expansion port on the front of the unit to accommodate them.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Two official advanced controllers were produced for the NES: the NES Advantage, an arcade controller produced by Asciiware and licensed by Nintendo of America; and the NES Max, a controller with grip handles and a "cycloid" sliding-disc D-pad in place of the traditional one.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Both controllers have a "Turbo" feature that simulates multiple rapid presses for the A and B buttons; the NES Max has manually pressed Turbo buttons, and the NES Advantage offers toggle buttons for Turbo functionality, along with knobs that adjust the firing rate of each button.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The latter also includes a "Slow" button that rapidly pauses games; however, this function is not intended for games that invoke a pause menu or screen.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The standard controller was redesigned for the introduction of the New-Style NES in 1993.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] This version retained detachable controller ports and the original button layout, but the shape was changed to loosely resemble that of the Super Famicom/SNES controller; its shape has led to it being nicknamed the "dog bone" controller.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo created a knitting machine that interfaced with the NES and showed it at CES in 1987 for "business feedback", although the accessory was ultimately not released as a product.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo spokesperson Howard Phillips demoed it for Toys "R" Us in the late 1980s, and an advertisement used the headline "Now you're knitting with power!" in reference to the slogan used by Nintendo at the time.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Few of the numerous peripheral devices and software packages for the Famicom were released outside Japan.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The Famicom 3D System, an active shutter 3D headset peripheral released in 1987, enabled the ability to play stereoscopic video games.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] It was a commercial failure and never released outside Japan; users described the headset as bulky and uncomfortable.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Seven games are compatible with the glasses, with three of them developed by Square; two titles received worldwide releases as *Rad Racer* and *The 3-D Battles of WorldRunner*.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The Family Computer Network System connected a Famicom to a now-defunct proprietary network in Japan which provided content such as financial services.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] A dial-up modem was reportedly being produced for the NES in a partnership with Fidelity Investments, but was ultimately not released.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] By 1986, the cost and size limitations of ROM chips used in the Famicom's ROM cartridges were apparent, with no new advancements present to address them.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] With this in mind, Nintendo looked at the personal computer (PC) market, where the floppy disk was gaining wide adoption as a computer data storage medium.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Partnering with Mitsumi to develop a floppy disk add-on for the Famicom based on the latter's Quick Disk format, Nintendo officially released it as the Family Computer Disk System (or Famicom Disk System) in Japan on February 21, 1986, at a retail price of ¥15,000.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The advantages of the format (called "Disk Card") were apparent on launch.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] It has more than triple the data storage capacity of the then-largest cartridge (used for *Super Mario Bros.*), introduced game save capability, and had lower production costs compared to cartridges, which resulted in lower retail prices.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The add-on also has a new wavetable synthesis sound channel and more data storage for the Famicom's audio sample channel.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Taking advantage of the disk's re-writability, Nintendo set up Disk Writer interactive kiosks at retail stores throughout Japan; at each kiosk, consumers could buy new games to rewrite onto their old disks or onto new disks.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Disk Fax kiosks allowed players to submit their high scores on special blue disks for contests and rankings, predating online leaderboards by several years.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Although Nintendo committed to exclusively releasing games on the Disk System after its release, numerous external issues plagued its long-term viability.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo also demanded half of the copyright ownership for each game it selected for release on the Disk System, resulting in developers electing to remain on cartridge instead as the latter gained functionality previously considered unique to the former.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Developers disliked the lower profit margin of the Disk Writer kiosks, and retailers complained of their use of valuable space as demand for the format waned.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Usage of a floppy disk-based medium brought about further complications; Disk Cards were more fragile than cartridges and were prone to data corruption from magnetic exposure.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Their unreliability was exacerbated by their lack of a shutter, which Nintendo substituted with a wax sleeve and clear keep case to reduce costs; blue disks and later Disk Cards included shutters.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The rubber belt-based disk drives were also unreliable, with cryptic error codes complicating troubleshooting; even when fully functional, players accustomed to cartridges were annoyed with the introduction of loading times and disk flipping.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Furthermore, the rewritable nature of the format resulted in rampant software piracy, with Nintendo's attempts at anti-piracy measures quickly defeated.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Despite selling close to two million Disk System units in 1986, Nintendo only managed to increase the total to 4.4 million units by 1990, falling well short of internal projections.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] By then, the Disk System was rendered obsolete due to advancements in ROM cartridge production, such as memory mapping chips for expanded data storage capacity, battery-backed SRAMTooltip static random-access memory for game saving, and declining overall production costs.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Nintendo alluded to a western release for the Disk System, going so far as to successfully file a US patent for it and having the Famicom's cartridge pins used by its RAM Adapter for enhanced audio rerouted to the NES's seldom-used bottom expansion port.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] However, such a release never materialized due to the Disk System's lackluster reception in Japan.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Most of its games were re-released with workarounds on cartridge for both the Famicom and NES, without the enhanced audio.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Although the last game for the Disk System was released in December 1992, Nintendo continued offering repair and rewrite services for it until September 2003.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The NES Test Station diagnostics machine, an NES-based unit designed for testing NES hardware, components, and games, was introduced in 1988.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] It was only provided for use in World of Nintendo boutiques as part of the Nintendo World Class Service program.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] Visitors were to bring items to test with the station, and could be assisted by a store technician or employee.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The NES Test Station's front has a Game Pak slot and connectors for testing various components (AC adapter, RF switch, Audio/Video cable, NES Control Deck, accessories and games), with a centrally located selector knob to choose which component to test.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The unit itself weighs approximately 5.3 kilograms (11.7 lb) and connects to a television via a combined A/V and RF Switch cable.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] By actuating the green button, a user can toggle between an A/V Cable or RF Switch connection.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p01] The television it is connected to (typically 11" to 14") is meant to be placed atop it.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p02] The NES uses a 72-pin design, compared to 60 pins on the Famicom.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p02] To reduce costs and inventory, some early games released in North America are simply Famicom cartridges attached to an adapter to fit inside the NES hardware.
[src:retro-6502-assembly/nintendo-entertainment-system-p02] Early NES cartridges are held together with five small slotted screws.
